{"title_page": "Heo Byeong-ho", "text_new": "{{short description|South Korean wrestler}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Heo Byeong-ho\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = South Korean\n| sport          = [[Wrestling]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1966|11|27|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Heo Byeong-ho''' (born 27 November 1966) is a South Korean [[amateur wrestling|wrestler]]. He competed at the [[1988 Summer Olympics]] and the [[1992 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/he/heo-byeong-ho-1.html |title=Heo Byeong-ho Olympic Results |accessdate=19 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heo, Byeong-ho}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:South Korean male sport wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Olympic wrestlers of South Korea]]\n[[Category:Wrestlers at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Wrestlers at the 1992 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{SouthKorea-wrestling-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South Korean wrestler}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Heo Byeong-ho\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = South Korean\n| sport          = [[Wrestling]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1966|11|27|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Heo Byeong-ho''' (born 27 November 1966) is a South Korean [[amateur wrestling|wrestler]]. He competed at the [[1988 Summer Olympics]] and the [[1992 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/he/heo-byeong-ho-1.html |title=Heo Byeong-ho Olympic Results |accessdate=19 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heo, Byeong-ho}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:South Korean male sport wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Olympic wrestlers of South Korea]]\n[[Category:Wrestlers at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Wrestlers at the 1992 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{SouthKorea-wrestling-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heo_Byeong-ho"}
{"title_page": "Rathdowney", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=July 2015}}\n{{for|the town of the same name in Queensland|Rathdowney, Queensland}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|settlement_type        = Village\n|name                   = Rathdowney\n|native_name             = {{Pad top italic|R\u00e1th Domhnaigh}}\n|image_skyline          = Rathdowney, Co. Laois, Ireland (View of Main Street).jpg\n|image_caption          = Main Street, Rathdowney\n|pushpin_map            = Ireland\n|pushpin_label_position = right\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Ireland\n|coordinates            = {{coord|52.8554|-7.5848|dim:100000_region:IE|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|blank_name_sec1        = Irish Grid Reference\n|blank_info_sec1        = {{iem4ibx|S279783}}\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = Ireland\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Ireland|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = Leinster\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Ireland|County]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[County Laois]]\n|unit_pref              = Metric\n|elevation_m            = 100\n|population_as_of       = 2016\n|population             = 1271\n|population_footnotes   = <ref name=\"census2016\">{{cite web|url = http://census.cso.ie/sapmap2016/Results.aspx?Geog_Type=ST2016&Geog_Code=0E6C7E99-5FFD-4F92-AAD3-AA7674DB6978#SAPMAP_T1_100 | publisher = Central Statistics Office | work = Census 2016 | title = Sapmap Area - Settlements - Rathdowney | date = April 2016 | accessdate = 28 January 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Rathdowney''' or '''Rathdowny''' ({{Irish place name|R\u00e1th Domhnaigh|ringfort of the church}})<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.logainm.ie/1416675.aspx | publisher = Irish Placenames Commission | title = R\u00e1th Domhnaigh / Rathdowney | accessdate = 28 January 2020}}</ref> is a town in southwest [[County Laois]], Ireland. It lies some 32&nbsp;km southwest of [[Portlaoise]] in the [[Irish Midlands]], at the point where the [[R433 road|R433]] [[Regional road (Ireland)|regional road]] from [[Abbeyleix]] to [[Templemore]] is crossed by the [[R435 road|R435]] from [[Borris-in-Ossory]] to [[Johnstown, County Kilkenny|Johnstown]]. The R433 provides access for Rathdowney to the Dublin-Cork [[M8 motorway (Ireland)|M8 motorway]], while the R435 links the town to the Dublin-Limerick [[M7 motorway (Ireland)|M7]].\nAs of the 2016 census, the population of Rathdowney was 1,271.<ref name=\"census2016\"/> Males in Rathdowney own more blow up dolls per capita than any other place\n\n==History==\nRathdowney is named after a nearby [[ringfort]], or ''r\u00e1th'', which was levelled in [[1830 in Ireland|1830]]. This r\u00e1th is mentioned three times in the [[Annals of the Four Masters]]:\n\n* 874 [[Flaithri]], son of [[Maelduin]], Lord of Rath-Tamhnaighe (Rathdowney) died\n* 909  [[Maelpadraig]], son of Flaithri, Lord of Rath-Tamhnaighe, died\n* 1069 [[Gillamoula]], grandson of [[Bruaideadh]], Lord of Rath-Tamhnaighe\n\nThe settlement of Rathdowney has existed since at least the 9th century. Historically it forms part of the [[Kingdom of Osraige]], and today it remains part of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Ossory]], as such Rathdowney is not historically part of Laois. The present-day county of Laois is a modern administrative construct.  A half mile southeast of Rathdowney, there stood until 1836, the ruins of a castle called Rathpiper, which most probably took its name from \"Pipard\", a descendant of Adam de Hereford.<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=cPMQAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA6&lpg=PA6&dq=rathpiper+castle+ireland#v=onepage&q=rathpiper%20castle%20ireland&f=false | title=The History and Antiquities of the Diocese of Ossory| isbn=9785879206463| last1=Carrigan| first1=William| year=1981}}</ref>  This locality of \"Pyperath\" within Rathdowny parish appears to have been a royal site associated with the medieval [[Mac Giolla Ph\u00e1draig dynasty]], as documents relating to meeting there in 1558 show.<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=cscQwIzZr70C&pg=PA24&lpg=PA24&dq=rathpiper+castle+ireland#v=onepage&q=rathpiper%20castle%20ireland&f=false |title = Royal Inauguration in Gaelic Ireland C. 1100-1600: A Cultural Landscape Study|isbn = 9781843830900|last1 = Fitzpatrick|first1 = Elizabeth|year = 2004}}</ref>\n\nThe Croppy's Grave located in the town's central square is the still visible cobbled grave of a [[croppy]] revolutionary hanged and buried there in 1798. The site also contains a recent memorial.\n\nThe town was raided at least once by anti-treaty forces during the [[Irish Civil War]] of 1922 to 1923.\n\n[[Queen Victoria]] passed through Rathdowney during her first visit to Ireland in 1849 and in a letter to her maternal sibling [[Princess Feodora of Leiningen]] about the visit to Ireland she described passing through a town assumed to be Rathdowney by historians as \"a quaint village, surrounded by hills\" and went on to describe it as \"an idyllic small town\".\n\n[[File:Rathdowney Panorama (Church St, Ossory St, Main St).jpg|thumb|Panorama of Rathdowney with Church Street on the left, Ossory Street to the centre, Main Street on the right]]\n\n==Churches==\nSaint Andrew's Church of Ireland church, which overlooks the town's square, was built in the early 19th century.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.buildingsofireland.ie/buildings-search/building/12900818/rathdowney-church-of-ireland-church-rathdowney-county-laois | publisher = National Inventory of Architectural Heritage | website = buildingsofireland.ie | title = Rathdowney Church Of Ireland Church, Rathdowney, County Laois | accessdate = 28 January 2020 }}</ref> It stands on the traditional site of an older Roman Catholic church, which was located there from medieval times until the Reformation. A new Catholic church was constructed on the main street in the 1830s, and this church served the Catholic population of the area for the next 120 years before it too was demolished; to be replaced by a shrine and carpark. A new larger Catholic church, the Church of the Holy Trinity, was designed by Simon Aloysius Leonard and built on the west side of the town in the 1950s.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.dia.ie/works/view/9798/CO.+LAOIS%2C+RATHDOWNEY%2C+CHURCH+%28RC%29 | publisher = Irish Architectural Archive | work = Dictionary of Irish Architects | title = Co. Laois, Rathdowney, Church (RC) | accessdate = 28 January 2020 }}</ref>\n\nThere are a number of \"mass pits\" (outdoor areas used for Catholic masses during penal times) located in the vicinity of the town.{{fact|date=January 2020}}\n\n==Economy==\nThe Meadow Meats processing plant is part of the Dawn Meats Group and was the largest employer in the town. This factory stands on the old Perry's Brewery site, it was purchased by Lyons Meats in 1968 and converted by them to a meat processing facility, which went into production in 1971. The largest employer currently is Dunnes Store Ltd.{{fact|date=January 2020}} Rathdowney is also something of a centre for several out lying villages and is a focal point for the surrounding agricultural hinterland.{{fact|date=January 2020}}\n\n==People==\n* [[John Moyney]], an Irish recipient of the [[Victoria Cross]], was born in Rathdowney. \n* [[James Pearson (soldier)|James Pearson]], also a [[Victoria Cross]] recipient from Rathdowney.\n* [[Kieran Phelan]], Irish Politician, seated in the Seanad 2002-2010.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of towns and villages in the Republic of Ireland|List of towns and villages in Ireland]]\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Rathdowney}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{County Laois}}\n\n[[Category:Towns and villages in County Laois]]\n[[Category:Townlands of County Laois]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=July 2015}}\n{{for|the town of the same name in Queensland|Rathdowney, Queensland}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|settlement_type        = Village\n|name                   = Rathdowney\n|native_name             = {{Pad top italic|R\u00e1th Domhnaigh}}\n|image_skyline          = Rathdowney, Co. Laois, Ireland (View of Main Street).jpg\n|image_caption          = Main Street, Rathdowney\n|pushpin_map            = Ireland\n|pushpin_label_position = right\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Ireland\n|coordinates            = {{coord|52.8554|-7.5848|dim:100000_region:IE|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|blank_name_sec1        = Irish Grid Reference\n|blank_info_sec1        = {{iem4ibx|S279783}}\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = Ireland\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Ireland|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = Leinster\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Ireland|County]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[County Laois]]\n|unit_pref              = Metric\n|elevation_m            = 100\n|population_as_of       = 2016\n|population             = 1271\n|population_footnotes   = <ref name=\"census2016\">{{cite web|url = http://census.cso.ie/sapmap2016/Results.aspx?Geog_Type=ST2016&Geog_Code=0E6C7E99-5FFD-4F92-AAD3-AA7674DB6978#SAPMAP_T1_100 | publisher = Central Statistics Office | work = Census 2016 | title = Sapmap Area - Settlements - Rathdowney | date = April 2016 | accessdate = 28 January 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Rathdowney''' or '''Rathdowny''' ({{Irish place name|R\u00e1th Domhnaigh|ringfort of the church}})<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.logainm.ie/1416675.aspx | publisher = Irish Placenames Commission | title = R\u00e1th Domhnaigh / Rathdowney | accessdate = 28 January 2020}}</ref> is a town in southwest [[County Laois]], Ireland. It lies some 32&nbsp;km southwest of [[Portlaoise]] in the [[Irish Midlands]], at the point where the [[R433 road|R433]] [[Regional road (Ireland)|regional road]] from [[Abbeyleix]] to [[Templemore]] is crossed by the [[R435 road|R435]] from [[Borris-in-Ossory]] to [[Johnstown, County Kilkenny|Johnstown]]. The R433 provides access for Rathdowney to the Dublin-Cork [[M8 motorway (Ireland)|M8 motorway]], while the R435 links the town to the Dublin-Limerick [[M7 motorway (Ireland)|M7]].\nAs of the 2016 census, the population of Rathdowney was 1,271.<ref name=\"census2016\"/>\n\n==History==\nRathdowney is named after a nearby [[ringfort]], or ''r\u00e1th'', which was levelled in [[1830 in Ireland|1830]]. This r\u00e1th is mentioned three times in the [[Annals of the Four Masters]]:\n\n* 874 [[Flaithri]], son of [[Maelduin]], Lord of Rath-Tamhnaighe (Rathdowney) died\n* 909  [[Maelpadraig]], son of Flaithri, Lord of Rath-Tamhnaighe, died\n* 1069 [[Gillamoula]], grandson of [[Bruaideadh]], Lord of Rath-Tamhnaighe\n\nThe settlement of Rathdowney has existed since at least the 9th century. Historically it forms part of the [[Kingdom of Osraige]], and today it remains part of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Ossory]], as such Rathdowney is not historically part of Laois. The present-day county of Laois is a modern administrative construct.  A half mile southeast of Rathdowney, there stood until 1836, the ruins of a castle called Rathpiper, which most probably took its name from \"Pipard\", a descendant of Adam de Hereford.<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=cPMQAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA6&lpg=PA6&dq=rathpiper+castle+ireland#v=onepage&q=rathpiper%20castle%20ireland&f=false | title=The History and Antiquities of the Diocese of Ossory| isbn=9785879206463| last1=Carrigan| first1=William| year=1981}}</ref>  This locality of \"Pyperath\" within Rathdowny parish appears to have been a royal site associated with the medieval [[Mac Giolla Ph\u00e1draig dynasty]], as documents relating to meeting there in 1558 show.<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=cscQwIzZr70C&pg=PA24&lpg=PA24&dq=rathpiper+castle+ireland#v=onepage&q=rathpiper%20castle%20ireland&f=false |title = Royal Inauguration in Gaelic Ireland C. 1100-1600: A Cultural Landscape Study|isbn = 9781843830900|last1 = Fitzpatrick|first1 = Elizabeth|year = 2004}}</ref>\n\nThe Croppy's Grave located in the town's central square is the still visible cobbled grave of a [[croppy]] revolutionary hanged and buried there in 1798. The site also contains a recent memorial.\n\nThe town was raided at least once by anti-treaty forces during the [[Irish Civil War]] of 1922 to 1923.\n\n[[Queen Victoria]] passed through Rathdowney during her first visit to Ireland in 1849 and in a letter to her maternal sibling [[Princess Feodora of Leiningen]] about the visit to Ireland she described passing through a town assumed to be Rathdowney by historians as \"a quaint village, surrounded by hills\" and went on to describe it as \"an idyllic small town\".\n\n[[File:Rathdowney Panorama (Church St, Ossory St, Main St).jpg|thumb|Panorama of Rathdowney with Church Street on the left, Ossory Street to the centre, Main Street on the right]]\n\n==Churches==\nSaint Andrew's Church of Ireland church, which overlooks the town's square, was built in the early 19th century.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.buildingsofireland.ie/buildings-search/building/12900818/rathdowney-church-of-ireland-church-rathdowney-county-laois | publisher = National Inventory of Architectural Heritage | website = buildingsofireland.ie | title = Rathdowney Church Of Ireland Church, Rathdowney, County Laois | accessdate = 28 January 2020 }}</ref> It stands on the traditional site of an older Roman Catholic church, which was located there from medieval times until the Reformation. A new Catholic church was constructed on the main street in the 1830s, and this church served the Catholic population of the area for the next 120 years before it too was demolished; to be replaced by a shrine and carpark. A new larger Catholic church, the Church of the Holy Trinity, was designed by Simon Aloysius Leonard and built on the west side of the town in the 1950s.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.dia.ie/works/view/9798/CO.+LAOIS%2C+RATHDOWNEY%2C+CHURCH+%28RC%29 | publisher = Irish Architectural Archive | work = Dictionary of Irish Architects | title = Co. Laois, Rathdowney, Church (RC) | accessdate = 28 January 2020 }}</ref>\n\nThere are a number of \"mass pits\" (outdoor areas used for Catholic masses during penal times) located in the vicinity of the town.{{fact|date=January 2020}}\n\n==Economy==\nThe Meadow Meats processing plant is part of the Dawn Meats Group and was the largest employer in the town. This factory stands on the old Perry's Brewery site, it was purchased by Lyons Meats in 1968 and converted by them to a meat processing facility, which went into production in 1971. The largest employer currently is Dunnes Store Ltd.{{fact|date=January 2020}} Rathdowney is also something of a centre for several out lying villages and is a focal point for the surrounding agricultural hinterland.{{fact|date=January 2020}}\n\n==People==\n* [[John Moyney]], an Irish recipient of the [[Victoria Cross]], was born in Rathdowney. \n* [[James Pearson (soldier)|James Pearson]], also a [[Victoria Cross]] recipient from Rathdowney.\n* [[Kieran Phelan]], Irish Politician, seated in the Seanad 2002-2010.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of towns and villages in the Republic of Ireland|List of towns and villages in Ireland]]\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Rathdowney}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{County Laois}}\n\n[[Category:Towns and villages in County Laois]]\n[[Category:Townlands of County Laois]]\n", "name_user": "80.233.50.164", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rathdowney"}
