illionaires|World's richest person]]|years=1996}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Hassanal Bolkiah]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Hassanal Bolkiah]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[The World's Billionaires|World's richest person]]|years=1998\u20132007}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Warren Buffett]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Warren Buffett]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[The World's Billionaires|World's richest person]]|years=2009}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Carlos Slim]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Carlos Slim]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[The World's Billionaires|World's richest person]]|years=2014\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jeff Bezos]]}}\n{{S-end}}}}\n{{Navboxes|title=Articles related to Bill Gates|list=\n {{Berkshire Hathaway}}\n {{Big History}}\n {{PadmaBhushanAwardRecipients 2010\u201319}}\n {{Time Persons of the Year 2001\u20132025}}\n {{World's richest people}}\n {{Jefferson Award Winners}}\n {{Members of the Chinese Academy of Engineering (2017)}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Subject bar|portal2=Renewable energy|portal3=Computer programming|commons=yes|n=yes|n-search=Category:Bill Gates|q=yes|d=yes|d-search=Q5284}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gates, Bill}}\n[[Category:Bill Gates| ]]\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century American engineers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American engineers]]\n[[Category:American billionaires]]\n[[Category:American chairmen of corporations]]\n[[Category:American computer businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American computer programmers]]\n[[Category:American corporate directors]]\n[[Category:American financiers]]\n[[Category:American humanitarians]]\n[[Category:American inventors]]\n[[Category:American investors]]\n[[Category:American nonprofit chief executives]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Scotch-Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:American philanthropists]]\n[[Category:American software engineers]]\n[[Category:American technology chief executives]]\n[[Category:American technology company founders]]\n[[Category:American technology writers]]\n[[Category:American venture capitalists]]\n[[Category:Big History]]\n[[Category:Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation people]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Seattle]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in software]]\n[[Category:People from Seattle]]\n[[Category:Cornell family]]\n[[Category:Directors of Berkshire Hathaway]]\n[[Category:Directors of Microsoft]]\n[[Category:Dudley\u2013Winthrop family]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the British Computer Society]]\n[[Category:Foreign members of the Chinese Academy of Engineering]]\n[[Category:Freemen of the City of London]]\n[[Category:Gates family]]\n[[Category:Giving Pledgers]]\n[[Category:21st-century philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Harvard College alumni]]\n[[Category:History of computing]]\n[[Category:History of Microsoft]]\n[[Category:Honorary Knights Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Lakeside School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States National Academy of Engineering]]\n[[Category:Microsoft employees]]\n[[Category:National Medal of Technology recipients]]\n[[Category:Nerd culture]]\n[[Category:People from Medina, Washington]]\n[[Category:Personal computing]]\n[[Category:Phillips family (New England)]]\n[[Category:Placards of the Order of the Aztec Eagle]]\n[[Category:Presidential Medal of Freedom recipients]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Cross of Recognition]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Bhushan in social work]]\n[[Category:Windows people]]\n[[Category:Wired (magazine) people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Seattle]]\n", "name_user": "Biscuit-in-Chief", "label": "safe", "comment": "\"second wealthiest\" --> \"second-wealthiest\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bill_Gates"}
{"title_page": "Andrea Luka Zimmerman", "text_new": "{{short description|Filmmaker and activist (b. 1969)}}\n\n{{Infobox artist\n| name = Andrea Luka Zimmerman\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = Andrea Luka Zimmerman\n| birth_date = 1969 <!-- {{1969} for living artists, {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}} for dead. For living people supply only the year unless the exact date is already WIDELY published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. Treat such cases as if only the year is known, so use {{birth year and age|YYYY}} or a similar option. -->\n| birth_place = Munich, Germany\n| nationality = British\n| alma_mater = {{nowrap|[[Central St Martins]] <small>([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]])</small><br />[[Central Saint Martins]] <small>([[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]])</small>}}\n| known_for = Vision Machine <br /> Fugitive Images\n| notable_works = [[Here For Life]]'' <br /> ''[[Erase and Forget]]'' <br /> ''Civil Rites'' <br /> ''Estate: A Reverie'' <br /> ''i am here''\n}}\n\n'''Andrea Luka Zimmerman''' (born 1969) is an artist and filmmaker. Zimmerman is most known for her work concerned with marginalisation, social justice and a search for radicalised re-relations, between people, place, ecology [https://www.studiointernational.com/index.php/andrea-luka-zimmerman-interview-here-for-life-film] <ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.artmonthly.co.uk/magazine/site/issue/october-2016 |title=Rules of Engagement &#124; |newspaper=[[Art Monthly]] |date=2016-10-20 |accessdate=2018-04-09}}</ref>. She is a Reader at [[Central Saint Martins|Central Saint Martins.]] Films include the [[Artangel]] produced ''[[Here For Life]]'' (2019), receiving Special Mention at the Cineasti Del Presente international competition of the 72nd [[Locarno Film Festival]], 2019, ''[[Erase and Forget]]'' (2017)<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.ft.com/content/e672cd0e-1c97-11e8-aaca-4574d7dabfb6 |title=Erase and Forget: portrait of a madcap American Hero &#124; |newspaper=[[The Financial Times]] |date=2018-02-28 |accessdate=2018-04-07}}</ref>, which had its world premiere at the [[Berlin Film Festival]] (nominated for the Glashutte Original Documentary Award), ''Estate, a Reverie'' (2015)<ref>{{cite web|last=Bechler |first=Rosemary |url=https://www.opendemocracy.net/opencitydocs/relationship-remembered |title= Relationship Remembered by Rosemary Bechler|website=opendemocracy.net |date=2015-06-14 |accessdate=2018-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artmonthly.co.uk/magazine/site/issue/october-2016|title=Art Monthly : Magazine : Issue : 400 October 2016|website=www.artmonthly.co.uk|access-date=2018-07-15}}</ref> and ''Taskafa, Stories'' of the Street (2013)<ref>{{Citation|last=Zimmerman|first=Andrea Luka|title=Tashkafa: Stories of the Street|date=2013-04-12|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2860362/|others=John Berger|access-date=2018-07-15}}</ref> which was written and voiced by [[John Berger]].        \n\n== Life and career ==\nAndrea Luka Zimmerman grew up on several large public housing estates, including the Wohnring in [[Neuperlach]], Germany, and left school at 16. After moving to London in 1991, she studied at [[Central Saint Martins]] for a PhD. She co-founded the film collective Vision Machine (collaborators on Academy Award\u00ae nominated feature documentary ''[[The Look of Silence]]''). Vision Machine was created in 2001 as an experimental filmmaking collective with the aim to research, analyse and respond to the conditions and mechanisms of economic, political and military power. Its members were Christine Cynn, [[Joshua Oppenheimer]], Michael Uwemedimo, Andrea Luka Zimmerman<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fugitiveimages.org.uk/projects/vision-machine.1/vision-machine-2001-2010  |title=Vision Machine 2001\u20132010 |access-date=2018-11-30}}</ref>. Zimmerman co-founded the cultural collective Fugitive Images, alongside Lasse Johansson and David Roberts in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fugitiveimages.org.uk/about/  |title=Fugitive Images |access-date=2018-11-30}}</ref>\n[[File:Andrea-Luka-Zimmerman-director-Here-For-Life-RTF-screening-Rio-Dalston-cinema-London-portrait-by-WIZ-19th-Feb-2020-0020.jpg|thumb|Andrea Luka Zimmerman, [https://www.birds-eye-view.co.uk/event/andrea-luka-zimmerman-and-adrian-jackson/ Rio Cinema, Reclaim The Frame], Anthony Wiz Johnson, 2020]]\nZimmerman's film ''Taskafa, Stories of the Street'' (2013, 66 minutes) explores resistance and co-existence through the lives of the street dogs of Istanbul.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://bostonreview.net/blog/simon-waxman-colin-dayan-dogs-edge-life|title=Colin Dayan's Ethics Without Reason &#124; |newspaper=[[Boston Review]] |date=2016-01-12 |accessdate=2018-07-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/on-killing-dogs/#!|title=On Killing Dogs &#124; |newspaper=[[LA Review of Books]] |date=2016-02-01 |accessdate=2018-07-11}}</ref> ''Estate, a Reverie'' (2015, 83 minutes) was made over seven years and tracks the passing of the [[Haggerston]] Estate in East London and the utopian promise of social housing it once offered, with a celebration of everyday humanity. ''[[Erase and Forget]]'' (2017, 86 minutes) was made over ten years and, through a documentary portrait of \"[[Bo Gritz]]\" explores the limits of deniability and social conscience in an age of constant warfare.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.anothergaze.com/the-discomfort-of-recognition-andrea-luka-zimmermans-erase-and-forget-2017-review/|title=The Discomfort of Recognition: Andrea Luka Zimmerman's ''Erase And Forget'' &#124; |newspaper=[[Another Gaze]] |date=2017-12-01 |accessdate=2018-07-11}}</ref> It premiered at the 2017 Berlin Film Festival.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/feb/13/erase-and-forget-documentary-bo-gritz|title=Erase and Forget: new documentary reveals life story of the real Rambo &#124; |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=2017-02-13 |accessdate=2018-07-11}}</ref> ''[https://www.artangel.org.uk/project/here-for-life/ Here for Life]'' (2019, 87mins) is a long term collaboration with theatre-maker and CEO of [[Cardboard Citizens]], [[Adrian Jackson (Cardboard Citizens)|Adrian Jackson]]. The film follows ten Londoners through a city framed by capital and loss, as they navigate their wild and wayward way, travelling on their own terms towards a co-existence far stronger than 'community'. On reclaimed land they find themselves on the right side of history, caught between two train tracks, the present tense and future hopes. They question who has stolen what from whom, and how things might be fixed, in an often contradictory rite of passage. Finding solidarity in resistance, they demand the right to go on.  \n\n[[File:Farewelll to the Haggerston estate .jpg|thumb|A 2013 procession passing the ''i am here'' artwork]]\nArt exhibitions and projects include ''[https://www.alamy.com/stock-photo-i-am-here-art-haggerston-estate-hackney-london-49120489.html i am here],'' a public artwork in [[Haggerston]], Hackney, which was made in response to the experience of living on a council estate which was being gentrified. For this, large photos of residents from the estate were placed over the windows of vacated flats, with the intention of opening up a \"reflective space concerning issues about visibility and 'urban regeneration'<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2009/sep/28/hackney-estate-public-art|title=Hackney estate: the faces in the windows|last=Saner|first=Emine|date=2009-09-27|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-02-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>.\" ''[http://www.peeruk.org/real-estates Real Estates]'' (co-curated with David Roberts), PEER with [[LUX]], London (2015), was a multifaceted project around issues of housing, social justice and public space in East London. ''[https://www.spikeisland.org.uk/programme/exhibitions/andrea-luka-zimmerman/ Common Ground,]'' Spike Island, Bristol (2017) comprised an exhibition, screening, talks and discussions around strategies of social and cultural resistance and ways of living together <ref name=\":0\" />. ''Civil Rites'' (2017) was made in response to a speech on the interlinked nature of \"war, poverty, racism\" given by [[Martin Luther King]] at Newcastle University, and was first shown at [[Tyneside Cinema]] Gallery in Newcastle in 2017/18, and [https://www.whitechapelgallery.org/exhibitions/the-london-open-2018/ London Open triennial] at [[Whitechapel Gallery]] in 2018.\n\n== Filmography ==\n*''The Delmarva Chicken of Tomorrow'' (short, 2003)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://film.britishcouncil.org/the-delmarva-chicken-of-tomorrow|title=British Council Film: The Delmarva Chicken of Tomorrow|website=film.britishcouncil.org|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref>\n*''The Globalisation Tapes'' (2003)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://lux.org.uk/work/the-globalization-tapes|title=The Globalization Tapes - LUX|work=LUX|access-date=2018-07-26}}</ref> (additional editor and camera)<ref>{{Citation|last=Anar|title=The Globalisation Tapes|date=2003|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0407827/|others=Intan Sinaga, Sharman Sinaga|access-date=2018-07-26|last2=Basir}}</ref>a collaboration between the Independent Plantation Workers' Union of Sumatra, the International Union of Food and Agricultural Workers (IUF), and Vision Machine\n*''The Last Biscuit'' (short, 2005)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/blu-rays-dvds/nighthawks-nighthawks-ii-strip-jack-naked|title=Nighthawks / Nighthawks II: Strip Jack Naked|website=British Film Institute|language=en|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref> a collaboration with [[imdbname:0356271|Paul Hallam]]\n*''The Ramp'' (short, 2010)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://film.britishcouncil.org/the-ramp|title=British Council Film: The Ramp|website=film.britishcouncil.org|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref>\n*''Merzschmerz'' (Film and Video Umbrella) (short, 2012)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fvu.co.uk/projects/merzschmerz|title=Film and Video Umbrella - Merzschmerz|website=www.fvu.co.uk|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref>\n*''Towards Estate'' (short, 2012)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/43937370|title=Towards Estate (Andrea Luka Zimmerman, 2012, 15min)|website=Vimeo|language=en|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref>\n*''Taskafa, Stories of the Street'' (2013)\n*''Estate, A Reverie'' (feature, 2015)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aestheticamagazine.com/art-prize/symposium-2016/|title=Aesthetica Magazine - Symposium 2016|website=Aesthetica Magazine|access-date=2018-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://conversations.e-flux.com/t/teleology-and-the-turner-prize-or-utility-the-new-conservatism/|title=Teleology and the Turner Prize or: Utility, the New Conservatism|website=e-flux conversations|access-date=2018-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/artsandculture/article/29191/1/watching-a-london-estate-being-dismantled-brick-by-brick|title=Watching a London estate being dismantled brick by brick|last=Dazed|date=2016-01-21|work=Dazed|access-date=2018-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.focaalblog.com/2015/04/23/andrea-luka-zimmerman-estates-of-being/|title=Andrea Luka Zimmerman: Estates of being: Thoughts on the place of living and working|website=www.focaalblog.com|access-date=2018-07-15}}</ref>\n*''More Utopias Now'' (Channel 4 Random Acts), (short, 2016)<ref>{{Citation|last=Random Acts|title=More Utopias Now - Andrea Luka Zimmerman|date=2017-09-11|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JCo3CQpFMio&t=1s|access-date=2018-07-15}}</ref>\n*''Lower Street, a Night\u2019s Journey'' (Tintype) (short, 2016)\n*''Civil Rites'' (Tyneside Cinema) (short, 2017)<ref>{{Citation|title=Civil Rites|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt7667310/|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thisistomorrow.info/articles/andrea-luka-zimmerman-civil-rites|title=Andrea Luka Zimmerman: Civil Rites|last=www.dandelion-burdock.com|first=dandelion & burdock|website=thisistomorrow|language=en|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mapmagazine.co.uk/civil-rites|title=Civil Rites|date=2018-02-01|website=MAP Magazine|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref>\n*''Erase and Forget'' (feature, 2017)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7tE884QU8gA|title=Going Underground &#124; |newspaper=[[Russia Today]] |date=2018-02-12 |accessdate=2018-07-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/w172vsqbp02nqrn|title=Weekend &#124; |newspaper=[[BBC World Service]] |date=2018-03-03 |accessdate=2018-07-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://eraseandforget.com/interviews/|title=Interviews \u2013 Erase and Forget|work=Erase and Forget|access-date=2018-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://eraseandforget.com/press/|title=Reviews and Press \u2013 Erase and Forget|work=Erase and Forget|access-date=2018-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sensesofcinema.com/2018/world-poll/world-poll-2017-part-6/|title=World Poll 2017 \u2013 Part 6 \u2022 Senses of Cinema|website=sensesofcinema.com|access-date=2018-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sensesofcinema.com/2018/world-poll/world-poll-2017-part-4/|title=World Poll 2017 - Part 4 \u2022 Senses of Cinema|website=sensesofcinema.com|access-date=2018-07-15}}</ref>\n*''Onions in the Plughole'' (short, 2018), on artist Marcia Farquhar [https://www.whitechapelgallery.org/events/marcia-farquhar-the-dogs-bolex/]\n*''Here For Life'' (Artangel) (feature, 2019) a collaboration with [[Adrian Jackson (Cardboard Citizens)|Adrian Jackson]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://film.britishcouncil.org/here-for-life|title=British Council Film: Here for Life|website=film.britishcouncil.org|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref>\n\n== Exhibitions and Projects ==\n*''i am here'' (Zimmerman, Johansson, Fennell), large scale public art work on the [[Haggerston|Haggerston Estate]] (2009\u20132014)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2009/sep/28/hackney-estate-public-art|title=Hackney estate: the faces in the windows|last=Saner|first=Emine|date=2009-09-27|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-02-24|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n*''Real Estates'' (co-curated with David Roberts), PEER Gallery, in association with LUX, London (2015)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://conversations.e-flux.com/t/teleology-and-the-turner-prize-or-utility-the-new-conservatism/|title=Teleology and the Turner Prize or: Utility, the New Conservatism|website=e-flux conversations|access-date=2018-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.peeruk.org/real-estates/|title=Real Estates at Peer Gallery}}</ref>\n*''Common Ground'' (solo), Spike Island, Bristol (2017)<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.spikeisland.org.uk/programme/exhibitions/andrea-luka-zimmerman/|title=Andrea Luka Zimmerman, Common Ground at Spike Island, Bristol|website=Spike Island|language=en|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref>\n*London Open (group), triennial at [[Whitechapel Gallery]] (2018)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0b5qnjs|title=Exam stress, Artist Andrea Luka Zimmerman, 50-50 music festivals, Woman's Hour - BBC Radio 4|website=BBC|access-date=2018-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thisistomorrow.info/articles/andrea-luka-zimmerman-civil-rites|title=Andrea Luka Zimmerman: Civil Rites|last=www.dandelion-burdock.com|first=dandelion & burdock|website=thisistomorrow|access-date=2018-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://narcmagazine.com/news-andrea-luka-zimmermans-civil-rites-tyneside-gallery/|title=NEWS: Andrea Luka Zimmerman's Civil Rites @ Tyneside Gallery|access-date=2018-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mapmagazine.co.uk/civil-rites|title=Civil Rites|date=2018-02-01|work=MAP Magazine|access-date=2018-07-15}}</ref>\n\n== Books ==\n*Co-author of ''Estate: Art, Politics and Social Housing in Britain'': Myrdle Court Press,''<nowiki/>'' 2010 {{ISBN|978-0-9563539-2-4}}\n*Contribution in ''Truth, Dare or Promise: Art and Document<nowiki/>ary Revisited''. London & New York: Cambridge Scholars Publishing, 2013, {{ISBN| 9781443849593}}. (Edit