{"title_page": "1942 Princeton Tigers football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox college sports team season\n| mode = football\n| year = 1942\n| team = Princeton Tigers\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| conference = Independent\n| record = 3\u20135\u20131\n| head_coach= [[Tad Wieman]]\n| hc_year = 5th\n| off_scheme = \n| def_scheme = \n| captain = Dick Schmon\n| stadium = [[Palmer Stadium]]\n}}\n{{1942 Eastern college football independents records}}\nThe '''1942 Princeton Tigers football team''' was an [[American football]] team that represented [[Princeton University]] as an independent during the [[1942 college football season]]. In its fifth and final season under head coach [[Tad Wieman]], the team compiled a 3\u20135\u20131 record and was outscored  by a total of 135 to 109. Dick Schmon was Princeton's team captain.<ref name=SR>{{cite web|title=1942 Princeton Tigers Schedule and Results|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=SR/College Football|accessdate=April 9, 2020|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/princeton/1942-schedule.html}}</ref><ref name=PMG>{{cite web|title=2008 Princeton Tigers Football Media Guide|publisher=Princeton University |page=127 |url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/sidearm.sites/princeton.sidearmsports.com/documents/2008/8/7/135152.pdf |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Princeton played its 1942 home games at [[Palmer Stadium]] in [[Princeton, New Jersey]].\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n|attend=y\n|source=y\n|rankyear=1942\n|poll=AP\n\n|September 26||[[Lakehurst Naval Air Station]]|[[Palmer Stadium]]|[[Princeton, New Jersey|Princeton, NJ]]|W 20-6||\n\n|October 3||{{cfb link|year=1942|team=Williams Ephs|title=Williams}}|Palmer Stadium|Princeton, NJ|L 7-19||\n\n|October 10|vs|[[1942 Navy Midshipmen football team|Navy]]|Yankee Stadium|[[The Bronx|Bronx, NY]]|W 10-0|25,000|<ref>{{cite news|title=Tigers Top Navy, 10-0; Frosh Stars|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=October 11, 1942|page=94|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48374031/tigers-top-navy-10-0-frosh-stars/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n|October 17|at|No. 8 [[1942 Penn Quakers football team|Penn]]|[[Franklin Field]]|[[Philadelphia|Philadelphia, PA]] ([[Penn\u2013Princeton football rivalry|rivalry]])|T 6-6||\n\n|October 24||[[1942 Brown Bears football team|Brown]]|Palmer Stadium|Princeton, NJ|W 32-13||\n\n|October 31|at|{{cfb link |year=1942 |team=Harvard Crimson|title=Harvard}}|[[Harvard Stadium]]|[[Boston|Boston, MA]] ([[Harvard\u2013Princeton football rivalry|rivalry]])|L 14-19||\n\n|November 7||{{cfb link |year=1942 |team=Dartmouth Indians|title=Dartmouth}}|Palmer Stadium|Princeton, NJ|W 7-19||\n\n|November 14|vs|[[1942 Yale Bulldogs football team|Yale]]|[[Baker Field]]|[[Manhattan|New York, NY]] ([[Princeton\u2013Yale football rivalry|rivalry]])|L 6-13|35,000|<ref>{{cite news|title=Elis Beat Tigers, 13-6|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=November 15, 1942|page=C42|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48374146/elis-beat-tigers-13-6/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n|November 21|vs|[[1942 Army Cadets football team|Army]]|Yankee Stadium|Bronx, NY|L 7-40|40,000|<ref>{{cite news|title=Army Batters Tiger, 40-7; Woods Stars|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=November 22, 1942|page=96|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48374275/army-batters-tiger-40-7-woods-stars/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Princeton Tigers football navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1942 Princeton Tigers football team}}\n[[Category:1942 college football season|Princeton]]\n[[Category:Princeton Tigers football seasons]]\n[[Category:1942 in sports in New Jersey|Princeton Football]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox college sports team season\n| mode = football\n| year = 1942\n| team = Princeton Tigers\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| conference = Independent\n| record = 3\u20135\u20131\n| head_coach= [[Tad Wieman]]\n| hc_year = 5th\n| off_scheme = \n| def_scheme = \n| captain = Dick Schmon\n| stadium = [[Palmer Stadium]]\n}}\n{{1942 Eastern college football independents records}}\nThe '''1942 Princeton Tigers football team''' was an [[American football]] team that represented [[Princeton University]] as an independent during the [[1942 college football season]]. In its fifth and final season under head coach [[Tad Wieman]], the team compiled a 3\u20135\u20131 record and was outscored  by a total of 135 to 109. Dick Schmon was Princeton's team captain.<ref name=SR>{{cite web|title=1942 Princeton Tigers Schedule and Results|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=SR/College Football|accessdate=April 9, 2020|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/princeton/1942-schedule.html}}</ref><ref name=PMG>{{cite web|title=2008 Princeton Tigers Football Media Guide|publisher=Princeton University |page=127 |url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/sidearm.sites/princeton.sidearmsports.com/documents/2008/8/7/135152.pdf |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Princeton played its 1942 home games at [[Palmer Stadium]] in [[Princeton, New Jersey]].\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n|attend=y\n|source=y\n|rankyear=1942\n|poll=AP\n\n|September 26||[[Lakehurst Naval Air Station]]|[[Palmer Stadium]]|[[Princeton, New Jersey|Princeton, NJ]]|W 20-6||\n\n|October 3||{{cfb link|year=1942|team=Williams Ephs|title=Williams}}|Palmer Stadium|Princeton, NJ|L 7-19||\n\n|October 10|vs|[[1942 Navy Midshipmen football team|Navy]]|Yankee Stadium|[[The Bronx|Bronx, NY]]|W 10-0|25,000|<ref>{{cite news|title=Tigers Top Navy, 10-0; Frosh Stars|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=October 11, 1942|page=94|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48374031/tigers-top-navy-10-0-frosh-stars/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n|October 17|at|No. 8 [[1942 Penn Quakers football team|Penn]]|[[Franklin Field]]|[[Philadelphia|Philadelphia, PA]] ([[Penn\u2013Princeton football rivalry|rivalry]])|T 6-6||\n\n|October 24||[[1942 Brown Bears football team|Brown]]|Palmer Stadium|Princeton, NJ|W 32-13||\n\n|October 31|at|{{cfb link |year=1942 |team=Harvard Crimson|title=Harvard}}|[[Harvard Stadium]]|[[Boston|Boston, MA]] ([[Harvard\u2013Princeton football rivalry|rivalry]])|L 14-19||\n\n|November 7||{{cfb link |year=1942 |team=Dartmouth Indians|title=Dartmouth}}|Palmer Stadium|Princeton, NJ|W 7-19||\n\n|November 14|vs|[[1942 Yale Bulldogs football team|Yale]]|[[Baker Field]]|[[Manhattan|New York, NY]] ([[Princeton\u2013Yale football rivalry|rivalry]])|L 6-13|35,000|<ref>{{cite news|title=Elis Beat Tigers, 13-6|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=November 15, 1942|page=C42|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48374146/elis-beat-tigers-13-6/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n|November 21|vs|[[1942 Army Cadets football team|Army]]|Yankee Stadium|Bronx, NY|L 7-40|40,000|<ref>{{cite news|title=Army Batters Tiger, 40-7; Woods Stars|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=November 22, 1942|page=96|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48374275/army-batters-tiger-40-7-woods-stars/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Princeton Tigers football navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1942 Princeton Tigers football team}}\n[[Category:1942 college football season|Princeton]]\n[[Category:Princeton Tigers football seasons]]\n[[Category:1942 in sports in New Jersey|Princeton Tigers football]]\n", "name_user": "Jweiss11", "label": "safe", "comment": "cat sort key", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1942_Princeton_Tigers_football_team"}
{"title_page": "David Leo", "text_new": "'''David Leo''' is a writer in Singapore. Leo received a Publishers Prize for ''Ah \u2026 The Fragrance of Durians & Other Stories'' in 1993, a (Singapore) National Book Department Council Book Awards for works in English in 1994 for ''The Sins of the Father''<ref>[http://www.ethosbooks.com.sg/store/mli_viewItem.asp?idProduct=92 Ethos Book Description] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071030205546/http://www.ethosbooks.com.sg/store/mli_viewItem.asp?idProduct=92 |date=2007-10-30 }}</ref> and [[Singapore Literature Prize]] commendation in 1995 for ''Wives, Lovers and Other Women''.<ref>[http://www.ethosbooks.com.sg/store/mli_viewItem.asp?idProduct=91 Ethos Books bio] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071030205803/http://www.ethosbooks.com.sg/store/mli_viewItem.asp?idProduct=91 |date=2007-10-30 }}</ref>\n\nHe is also the author of ''Different Strokes'', a novel published in 1993 on two [[AIDS]] victims and a reporter who interviews them. The novel explores societal views on AIDS and its victims.\n\nSome of David's short stories have won prizes in writing competitions in Singapore. He also writes poetry; some of his poems have appeared in various publications including Singa, Focus, Breakthrough, ''Project Alpha Silver'', and an anthology of 20th Century Poets published in the UK\n\nLeo works as an [[Assistant General Manager]] at the [[Singapore Airport Terminal Services]].\n\n==Works==\n===Different Strokes===\n''Different Strokes'' is a novel written by David Leo and published in 1993. Through a character of a reporter named Keith, the novel explores the life of two [[AIDS]] victims, and describes their suffering and the dilemmas they face in the course of their illness. The work is among the earliest work in [[Singapore]] related to the gay community.{{Citation needed|date=March 2008}}\n\n=== Novels, short stories and non-fiction  ===\n* ''Somewhere a Tiny Voice'' (1993)\n* ''Ah ... the Fragrance of Durians''' (1993)\n* ''The Sins of the Father and Other Stories'' (1993)\n* ''Different Strokes'' (1993)\n* ''Wives, Lovers & Other Women'' (1995)\n* ''Kiasu, Kiasi, You Think What'' (1995) {{ISBN|981-204-626-7}} (see [[Kiasu]])\n* ''One Journey, Many Rivers'' (1997)\n* ''Shakespeare Can Wait'' (2001)\n* ''News at Nine'' (2003)\n* ''Life's So Like Dat'' (2005)\n* ''iDENTiTY'' (2008)\n* ''Ubin Dreaming (You've Been Dreaming)'' (2012)\n* ''Cherry Days'' (2015)\n\n=== Anthologies  ===\n* No Other City \u2013 The Ethos Anthology of Urban Poetry\n* Love Gathers All \u2013 The Philippines-Singapore Anthology of Love Poetry\n* Rhythms \u2013 A Singapore Anthology of Millenium Poetry\n* Man/Born/Free: Writings on the Human Spirit from Singapore (edited by Gwee Li Sui)\n* OnE, The Anthology \u2013 Short Stories from Singapore's best authors (edited by Robert Yeo)\n* Sound of Mind \u2013 A teacher-writers anthology of poems and prompts\n* Influence and Confluence: East and West / A Global Anthology on the Short Story (edited by Maurice A Lee), East\n* China Normal University Press (Story was also translated into Chinese) {{ISBN|978-7-5675-5183-1}}\n* 20th Century Poets\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|LGBT}}\n\n* [[Singapore gay literature]]\n* [[Gay literature]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070710024730/http://www.thecore.nus.edu.sg/post/singapore/literature/poetry/leo/bio1.html Bio of David Leo]\n*[http://www.ethosbooks.com.sg/search?q=david+leo Publisher's website]\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leo, David}}\n[[Category:Singaporean writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Singaporean novelists]]\n[[Category:Singaporean male writers]]\n[[Category:Singaporean non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Singapore Literature Prize winners]]\n\n\n{{Singapore-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''David Leo''' is a writer in Singapore. Leo received a Publishers Prize for ''Ah \u2026 The Fragrance of Durians & Other Stories'' in 1993, a (Singapore) National Book Department Council Book Awards for works in English in 1994 for ''The Sins of the Father''<ref>[http://www.ethosbooks.com.sg/store/mli_viewItem.asp?idProduct=92 Ethos Book Description] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071030205546/http://www.ethosbooks.com.sg/store/mli_viewItem.asp?idProduct=92 |date=2007-10-30 }}</ref> and [[Singapore Literature Prize]] commendation in 1995 for ''Wives, Lovers and Other Women''.<ref>[http://www.ethosbooks.com.sg/store/mli_viewItem.asp?idProduct=91 Ethos Books bio] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071030205803/http://www.ethosbooks.com.sg/store/mli_viewItem.asp?idProduct=91 |date=2007-10-30 }}</ref>\n\nHe is also the author of ''Different Strokes'', a novel published in 1993 on two [[AIDS]] victims and a reporter who interviews them. The novel explores societal views on AIDS and its victims.\n\nSome of David's short stories have won prizes in writing competitions in Singapore. He also writes poetry; some of his poems have appeared in various publications including Singa, Focus, Breakthrough, ''Project Alpha Silver'', and an anthology of 20th Century Poets published in the UK\n\nLeo works as an [[Assistant General Manager]] at the [[Singapore Airport Terminal Services]].\n\n==Works==\n===Different Strokes===\n''Different Strokes'' is a novel written by David Leo and published in 1993. Through a character of a reporter named Keith, the novel explores the life of two [[AIDS]] victims, and describes their suffering and the dilemmas they face in the course of their illness. The work is among the earliest work in [[Singapore]] related to the gay community.{{Citation needed|date=March 2008}}\n\n=== Novels, short stories and non-fiction  ===\n* ''Somewhere a Tiny Voice'' (1993)\n* ''Ah ... the Fragrance of Durians''' (1993)\n* ''The Sins of the Father and Other Stories'' (1993)\n* ''Different Strokes'' (1993)\n* ''Wives, Lovers & Other Women'' (1995)\n* ''Kiasu, Kiasi, You Think What'' (1995) {{ISBN|981-204-626-7}} (see [[Kiasu]])\n* ''One Journey, Many Rivers'' (1997)\n* ''Shakespeare Can Wait'' (2001)\n* ''News at Nine'' (2003)\n* ''Life's So Like Dat'' (2005)\n* ''iDENTiTY'' (2008)\n* ''Ubin Dreaming (You've Been Dreaming)'' (2012)\n* ''Cherry Days'' (2015)\n\n=== Anthologies  ===\n* No Other City \u2013 The Ethos Anthology of Urban Poetry\n* Love Gathers All \u2013 The Philippines-Singapore Anthology of Love Poetry\n* Rhythms \u2013 A Singapore Anthology of Millenium Poetry\n* Man/Born/Free: Writings on the Human Spirit from Singapore (edited by Gwee Li Sui)\n* OnE, The Anthology \u2013 Short Stories from Singapore's best authors (edited by Robert Yeo)\n* Sound of Mind \u2013 A teacher-writers anthology of poems and prompts\n* Influence and Confluence: East and West / A Global Anthology on the Short Story (edited by Maurice A Lee), East\n* China Normal University Press (Story was also translated into Chinese) {{ISBN|978-7-5675-5183-1}}\n* 20th Century Poets\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|LGBT}}\n\n* [[Singapore gay literature]]\n* [[Gay literature]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070710024730/http://www.thecore.nus.edu.sg/post/singapore/literature/poetry/leo/bio1.html Bio of David Leo]\n*[http://www.ethosbooks.com.sg/search?q=david+leo Publisher's website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leo, David}}\n[[Category:Singaporean writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Singaporean novelists]]\n[[Category:Singaporean male writers]]\n[[Category:Singaporean non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Singapore Literature Prize winners]]\n\n\n{{Singapore-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Leo"}
{"title_page": "The Medal for the Martyrs", "text_new": "'''The Medal for the Martyrs''' ([[Kurdish languages|Kurdish]]: Medal j\u00ee bo \u015eeh\u00eed) is a commemorative international decoration ([[medal]]) and project to commemorate the international fighters and volunteers with the [[Kurds|Kurdish]] forces killed while in [[Syria]]<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://internationalistcommune.com/internationalist-sehids/|title=Internationalist Sehids|last=|first=|date=2020|website=Internationalist  Commune|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref> or who died as a result of their service in Syria.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allbadges.net/en/badge/32927|title=The Medal for the Martyrs|last=|first=|date=1 February 2020|website=All Badges|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=128433091928419&id=102385111199884&__xts__[0]=68.ARDQLLyZGi30J3UmxlfApZtqsEALHmYlWPT11Yvtw28xegC2TXKzwOPX9fIZL6XfMh2QewEialtvv_vMkHCG8yvVuX7xfD0spNL8lkDkFV-Xtk3IP8o_oGjkT9FAsdHv6JuwOSvH58yF6uryUWTSWetCaBP_HhkDKF2BKMcVsuiy3dmz5yy4r012O9qHo2Dom164kcqO_Oh7d2ycw69VtUxJSkbJnHj8VV8Fe9jpOSYeAh83Sd4qEQbMBcFRRz6TxsIpkVl6_fzMZ-ltZvhY9s7zKNiQDi3GoqQcf7zvahJN8IvpphM4hXfyAYyVdvF6ZLpDTcVlx1zx-n-eBmY&__tn__=-R|title=The Medal for the Martyrs Facebook post|last=|first=|date=28 November 2019|website=Facebook|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{Infobox military award|name=The Medal for the Martyrs<br/>{{lang|ku|Medal j\u00ee bo \u015eeh\u00eed}}|first_award=April, 2020|alt2=|image2=File:The Medal for the Marty Ribbon.png|related=|lower=|same=|higher=|individual=|precedence_label=|recipients=|posthumous=All (15)|total=15|last_award=|established=February, 2019|image=The Medal for the Martyrs - Specimen.jpg|post-nominals=|clasps=|motto={{lang|ku|\u015eEH\u00ceD NAMIRIN}} (\"Martyrs Never Die\")|description=Medal diameter: 34mm\nThickness: 3mm\nRibbon width: 32mm|status=Awarded as necessary|campaign=[[Syrian Civil War]]; [[Syrian Kurdish\u2013Islamist conflict (2013\u2013present)]]|for=Killed or died as a result of their service in Syria (Rojava)|eligibility=Foreign volunteers with SDF, YPG or YPJ forces|type=Commemorative medal ([[decoration]])|country=[[Rojava]]|awarded_by=foreign volunteers of the [[Syrian Democratic Forces]], [[People's Protection Units]] and the [[Women's Protection Units]]|caption=Obverse (left) and reverse (right) of The Medal for the Martyrs.|alt=|caption2=[[Medal ribbon|Ribbon bar]]}}\n\n== Award criteria ==\n\n==== Medal ====\nThe medal is presented to the families (next of kin) of foreign fighters and volunteers with the Kurdish [[Syrian Democratic Forces]] (SDF), [[People's Protection Units]] (YPG) or [[Women's Protection Units]] (YPJ) forces in Syria who were killed while fighting against the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL) or Turkish forces. The families of international fighters and volunteers who after returning home died as a direct result of their service (such as in the case of a suicide relating to [[Posttraumatic stress disorder|PTSD]]) are also eligible to receive a medal.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==== Ribbon bar ====\nA ribbon bar was not issued with the medal. Instead a small number were made and presented to those that significantly contributed to the project as a token of gratitude.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allbadges.net/en/badge/33301|title=The Medal for the Martyrs - Ribbon Bar|last=|first=|date=22 February 2020|website=All Badges|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== The Project ==\n\n==== Initial concept ====\nThe initial concept first came about in February 2019 as an idea of SDF and YPG veteran Daniel Bourke and an Australian friend with a background in [[numismatics]]. They came up with the idea to use an ISIL 25 fals coin and repurpose it as a medal to commemorate the fallen international fighters and volunteers. The initial medal construction involved having an actual ISIL 25 fals coin (as opposed to a replica) joined to a suspension bar. This was not able to be done because the disc and suspension bar in modern medal production are made as one meaning that medal manufacturers refused to make a separate suspension bar and then join it to the coin. Another issue was that not enough coins could be sourced in time to make the right number of medals.\n\n==== Project launch ====\nAfter consulting with other international veterans and related groups, the design was updated and a [[social media]] campaign on both [[Facebook]] and [[Instagram]] was launched. The official camping and project was launched on the 12th of November, 2019, the day after [[Remembrance Day]] and [[Veterans Day]] to help raise awareness of the project and of the international fighters and volunteers who were lost.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/The-Medal-for-the-Martyrs-102385111199884/|title=The Medal for the Martyrs - Facebook|last=|first=|date=12 November 2019|website=Facebook|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Funding ====\nOn 10 December 2019 a [[GoFundMe]] camping was started to raise funds for the project. The campaign was promoted through the Facebook page and Instagram account. The campaign has been unsuccessfully with only raising $490 [[Australian dollar|AUD]] to date.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.the-medal-for-the-martyrs|title=The Medal for the Martyrs - GoFundMe|last=|first=|date=10 December 2019|website=GoFundMe|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 January 2020}}</ref> To deal with this it was decided that a small initial order of medal would be ordered and mostly payed for by one of the project organisers in Australia.\n\n==== First issue ====\nOn 31 of January, 2020 it was posted on both the Facebook page and Instagram account that the first order of medals have been placed and in production.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/102385111199884/photos/a.128980338540361/159489875489407/?type=3&theater|title=The Medal for the Martyrs Facebook post|last=|first=|date=31 January 2020|website=Facebook|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 January 2020}}</ref> on the 8 of April, 2020 It was announced on both the Facebook page and Instagram account the first issue of medals had been received and the first few were being sent out.\n\n== Design ==\n\nThe Medal for the Martyrs is constructed around a replica of a captured bronze 25 fals coin that was made and used by ISIL within [[ISIL territorial claims|territory under their control]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/jenanmoussa/status/881226717657956352|title=1/ #BREAK: I obtained a silver ISIS coin. This is 1st concrete evidence that ISIS indeed introduced own currency in areas of its control|last=Moussa|first=Jenan|date=1 July 2017|website=Twitter - Reporter Jenan Moussa|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|dead-url=}}</ref> The metal disc and suspension bar are made as one from a zine die cast and plated bronze with a brushed finish applied. A ribbon is threaded through the suspension bar with a brooch attached behind at the top.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe idea to use a captured coin for the medal was inspired by the Australian [[Battle of Cocos|Sydney Emden medal]] and the idea to reappropriate the ISIL coin came from the reappropriation of the [[Nazi Germany]] [[Iron Cross#World War II|1939 Iron Cross]] medal's ribbon for the Israeli [[Fighters against Nazis Medal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fighters_against_Nazis_Medal|title=Fighters against Nazis Medal|last=|first=|date=|website=Wikipedia|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|dead-url=}}</ref>\n\nIt was an intentional decision for the medal to replicate an ISIL 25 fals coin as many of these and other similar coins were taken and confiscated by fighters in areas that were liberated from ISIL. ISIL's name and motto from the obverse side were removed and replaced with the acronyms of the three main Kurdish forces and a motto. This was deliberately done to show the liberation of and destruction of ISIL's so-called \"[[caliphate]]\" as well as symbolising an attack on and eradication of their extremist and harmful ideology.\n\nThe medal was manufactured and assembled by Cash's Awards and Promotion Solutions located in [[Frankston, Victoria|Frankston]], [[Australia]]. \n[[File:ISIS_25_Ful\u00fbs_coin_obverse.jpg|thumb|The obverse side of the ISIL 25 fals coin that the medal's obverse design was modelled from.]]\n\n==== Obverse ====\nThe obverse of the medal is a replica of the obverse side of an ISIL 25 fals coin. The medal reads at the top \"YPG SDF YPJ\" representing the three main forces that the volunteers were part of. This top line also replaces the original Arabic on the coin that read \"\u0627\u0644\u062f\u0648\u0644\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\u064a\u0629\" (The Islamic State).<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://english.religion.info/2018/12/23/the-return-of-the-gold-dinar-an-analysis-of-the-islamic-state-coin-production/|title=The Return of the Gold Dinar \u2013 An analysis of the Islamic State coin production|last=Moos|first=Olivier|date=23 December 2018|website=Religioscope|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|dead-url=}}</ref> The bottom line reads in [[Kurdish languages|Kurdish]] a saying and motto \"\u015eEH\u00ceD NAMIRIN\" (Martyrs Never Die). The motto replaces ISIL's motto that was on the coin \"\u062e\u0644\u0627\u0641\u0629 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u0645\u0646\u0647\u0627\u062c \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0628\u0648\u0629\" (A caliphate upon prophetic methodology).<ref name=\":1\" /> The area around the text \"YPG SDF YPJ\" and \"\u015eEH\u00ceD NAMIRIN\" is slightly sunken into the surface of the medal to create the illusion that the new text has been overstruck on the original text, symbolising an eradication of ISIL and other hostile entities. In the centre is the coin's value (25 fals) \"\u0662\u0665 \u0641\u0644\u0633\u0627\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://en.numista.com/catalogue/pieces154096.html|title=25 Falsan (thin variety)|last=|first=|date=|website=Numista|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|dead-url=}}</ref> within a segmented circle. To the centre right is the coin's original weight (15 grams) \"\u0661\u0665 \u063a\u0631\u0627\u0645\";<ref name=\":0\" /> and to the centre left is the coin's original metal content \"\u0646\u062d\u0627\u0633\" (copper).<ref name=\":0\" /> The coin's denomination, weight and metal composition were kept on the medal to create the illusion that the medal was made using a coin. \n[[File:ISIS_25_Ful\u00fbs_coin_reverse.jpg|thumb|The reverse side of the ISIL 25 fals coin that the medal's reverse design was modelled from.]]\n\n==== Reverse ====\nThe reverse of the medal is a replica of the reverse side of an ISIL 25 fals coin. At the centre is the [[Islamic calligraphy]] of a [[Hadith]] and below is the [[Gregorian calendar|Gregorian]] year in Arabic text of the year that the medal was first issued in \"\u0662\u0660\u0662\u0660\" (2020); all surrounded by a pattern of interwoven curved lines. The Hadith reads in Arabic \"\u0623\u0641\u0636\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0635\u062f\u0642\u0629 \u062c\u0647\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0642\u0644\", which translates to in English as \"The best charity is the effort of the less wealthy\".<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOne of the reasons why this Hadith was placed on the coin by ISIL was to use Islamic teachings and beliefs to pursued the people under their control to donate these coins back towards their cause. The main reasons why it was decided to keep it on the medal was that it preaches the importance of charity which can be interpreted to preach how important it was for the recipients to volunteer themselves and ultimately pay the highest price for there acts of charity for the Kurdish, Syrian and Iraqi peoples.\n\n==== Ribbon ====\nThe ribbon in 32&nbsp;mm wide. At the centre is a 4mm red ([[Pantone#Pantone Color Matching System|Pantone]] 108) stripe flanked on either side by black (Pantone Black) stripes to symbolise the blood and loss of those that were killed. On either side of the central stripes are two 3mm light brown (Pantone 1205) stripes representing the sandy desert terrain of Syria. On the left is a 5mm yellow (Pantone Yellow) stripe flanked on both sides by 2mm green (Pantone 350) stripes, representing the flag of the YPG. On the right is a 5mm green (Pantone 350) stripe flanked on both sides by 2mm yellow (Pantone Yellow) stripes, representing the flag of the YPJ.\n\nYellow, red and green also makeup the tricolour [[Flag of North and East Syria]] which is used by the [[Movement for a Democratic Society]] (TEV-DEM), the political coalition that governs the [[Autonomous Administration of North and East Syria]] (NES) also known as [[Rojava]].\n\n==== Suspension bar ====\nOn the front facing side of the suspension bar is the boxed in text \"ROJAVA\", the Kurdish name of the semi-autonomous region of north-eastern Syria and the main region in which the recipients fought in. Connecting the suspension bar to the disc is a five-pointed star, the same that is used on many Kurdish flags such as those of the YPG and YPJ. The back side has the laser engraved name of the recipient.\n\n== Recipients ==\nThe following is a table detailing all the recipients of the medal.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ypg-international.org|title=YPG International|last=|first=|date=2019|website=YPG International|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|dead-url=}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+First Issue: April 2020\n!Name\n!Nom de guerre\n!Date and Place fo Birth\n!Date and Place of Death\n!Additional Comments\n|-\n|Reece Harding\n|Bagok Serhed\n|31 August 1991, Middle Swan, Western Australia, Australia\n|27 June 2015, Gir\u00easp\u00ee, Sil\u00fbk, Gund\u00ea Genter\u00ee\n|\n|-\n|John Robert Gallagher\n|Gaber Rojava\n|30 September 1983, Toronto, Canada\n|4 November 2015, Heseke, Al-Hol\n|\n|-\n|Jamie Bright\n|Gaber Amed\n|1971, Australia\n|25 May 2016, Sadaddi, Gund\u00ea Malha, Northern Syria\n|\n|-\n|Daniel Pascual\n|Heval Amor\n|29 May 1993, Barcelona, Espa\u00f1a\n|12 July 2016, Sant Antoni De Vilamajor, Espa\u00f1a\n|Passed after returning home.\n|-\n|Levi Jonathan Shirley\n|Ag\u00eer Servan\n|Nevada, United States\n|14 July 2016, Minbic, Northern Syria\n|\n|-\n|Dean Carl Evans\n|Givara Rojava\n|Reading, United Kingdom\n|21 July 2016, Minbic, Northern Syria\n|\n|-\n|Ryan Lock\n|Berxwedan G\u00eevara\n|26 June 1996, Chichester, United Kingdom\n|21 December 2016, Raqqa, Northern Syria\n|\n|-\n|Paolo Todd\n|Kawa Amed\n|Los Angeles, United States\n|15 January 2017, Raqqa, Northern Syria\n|\n|-\n|[[Robert Grodt]]\n|Demhat Goldman\n|February 1989, California, United States\n|6 July 2017, Raqqa, Northern Syria\n|\n|-\n|Luke Rutter\n|Soro Zinar\n|Birkenhead, United Kingdom\n|6 July 2017, Raqqa, Northern Syria\n|\n|-\n|Farid Medjahed\n|Sah\u00een Qer\u00e7ox\n|Marselles, France\n|6 October 2017, Deir al-Zour, North Eastern Syria\n|\n|-\n|[[Jac Holmes]]\n|Sores Amanos\n|18 January 1993, Pool, United Kingdom\n|23 October 2017, Raqqa, Syria\n|\n|-\n|[[Oliver Hall (YPG fighter)|Ollie Hall]]\n|Can\u015f\u00ear Zagros\n|28 October 1993, United Kingdom\n|25 November 2017, Raqqa, Northern Syria\n|Two medals were produced, one for each of Ollie's parents who are divorced. Each medal is named \"Olivier Hall\" followed by either \"1/2\" or \"2/2\".\n|-\n|Sjoerd Heeger\n|Baran Sason\n|1993, Helmond, Netherlands\n|12 February 2018, Afrin, Rojava\n|\n|-\n|Kevin Howard\n|\n|23 September 1988, Grants Pass, Oregon, United States\n|30 March 2019, Tucson, Arizona, United States\n|Passed after returning home.\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" |An additional medal were produced with \"SPECIMEN\" laser engraved on the back of the suspension bar.\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Foreign fighters in the Syrian and Iraqi Civil Wars]]\n* [[International Freedom Battalion]]\n* [[List of military awards and decorations of the international military intervention against ISIL]]\n* [[Rojava conflict]]\n* [[Syrian Civil War]]\n* [[Syrian Kurdish\u2013Islamist conflict (2013\u2013present)]]\n* [[YPG International]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n{{Phaleristics}}\n\n<!--     CATEGORIES     -->\n[[Category:Awards honoring women| ]]\n[[Category:Martyrdom]]\n[[Category:Martyrs' monuments and memorials|*01]]\n[[Category:Martyrs]]\n[[Category:Posthumous recognitions]]\n[[Category:Wound decorations]]\n", "text_old": "'''The Medal for the Martyrs''' ([[Kurdish languages|Kurdish]]: Medal j\u00ee bo \u015eeh\u00eed) is a commemorative international decoration ([[medal]]) and project to commemorate the international fighters and volunteers with the [[Kurds|Kurdish]] forces killed while in [[Syria]]<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://internationalistcommune.com/internationalist-sehids/|title=Internationalist Sehids|last=|first=|date=2020|website=Internationalist  Commune|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref> or who died as a result of their service in Syria.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allbadges.net/en/badge/32927|title=The Medal for the Martyrs|last=|first=|date=1 February 2020|website=All Badges|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=128433091928419&id=102385111199884&__xts__[0]=68.ARDQLLyZGi30J3UmxlfApZtqsEALHmYlWPT11Yvtw28xegC2TXKzwOPX9fIZL6XfMh2QewEialtvv_vMkHCG8yvVuX7xfD0spNL8lkDkFV-Xtk3IP8o_oGjkT9FAsdHv6JuwOSvH58yF6uryUWTSWetCaBP_HhkDKF2BKMcVsuiy3dmz5yy4r012O9qHo2Dom164kcqO_Oh7d2ycw69VtUxJSkbJnHj8VV8Fe9jpOSYeAh83Sd4qEQbMBcFRRz6TxsIpkVl6_fzMZ-ltZvhY9s7zKNiQDi3GoqQcf7zvahJN8IvpphM4hXfyAYyVdvF6ZLpDTcVlx1zx-n-eBmY&__tn__=-R|title=The Medal for the Martyrs Facebook post|last=|first=|date=28 November 2019|website=Facebook|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{Infobox military award|name=The Medal for the Martyrs<br/>{{lang|ku|Medal j\u00ee bo \u015eeh\u00eed}}|first_award=April, 2020|alt2=|image2=File:The Medal for the Marty Ribbon.png|related=|lower=|same=|higher=|individual=|precedence_label=|recipients=|posthumous=All (15)|total=15|last_award=|established=February, 2019|image=The Medal for the Martyrs - Specimen.jpg|post-nominals=|clasps=|motto={{lang|ku|\u015eEH\u00ceD NAMIRIN}} (\"Martyrs Never Die\")|description=Medal diameter: 34mm\nThickness: 3mm\nRibbon width: 32mm|status=Awarded as necessary|campaign=[[Syrian Civil War]]; [[Syrian Kurdish\u2013Islamist conflict (2013\u2013present)]]|for=Killed or died as a result of their service in Syria (Rojava)|eligibility=Foreign volunteers with SDF, YPG or YPJ forces|type=Commemorative medal ([[decoration]])|country=[[Rojava]]|awarded_by=foreign volunteers of the [[Syrian Democratic Forces]], [[People's Protection Units]] and the [[Women's Protection Units]]|caption=Obverse (left) and reverse (right) of The Medal for the Martyrs.|alt=|caption2=[[Medal ribbon|Ribbon bar]]}}\n\n== Award criteria ==\n\n==== Medal ====\nThe medal is presented to the families (next of kin) of foreign fighters and volunteers with the Kurdish [[Syrian Democratic Forces]] (SDF), [[People's Protection Units]] (YPG) or [[Women's Protection Units]] (YPJ) forces in Syria who were killed while fighting against the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL) or Turkish forces. The families of international fighters and volunteers who after returning home died as a direct result of their service (such as in the case of a suicide relating to [[Posttraumatic stress disorder|PTSD]]) are also eligible to receive a medal.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==== Ribbon bar ====\nA ribbon bar was not issued with the medal. Instead a small number were made and presented to those that significantly contributed to the project as a token of gratitude.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allbadges.net/en/badge/33301|title=The Medal for the Martyrs - Ribbon Bar|last=|first=|date=22 February 2020|website=All Badges|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== The Project ==\n\n==== Initial concept ====\nThe initial concept first came about in February 2019 as an idea of SDF and YPG veteran Daniel Bourke and an Australian friend with a background in [[numismatics]]. They came up with the idea to use an ISIL 25 fals coin and repurpose it as a medal to commemorate the fallen international fighters and volunteers. The initial medal construction involved having an actual ISIL 25 fals coin (as opposed to a replica) joined to a suspension bar. This was not able to be done because the disc and suspension bar in modern medal production are made as one meaning that medal manufacturers refused to make a separate suspension bar and then join it to the coin. Another issue was that not enough coins could be sourced in time to make the right number of medals.\n\n==== Project launch ====\nAfter consulting with other international veterans and related groups, the design was updated and a [[social media]] campaign on both [[Facebook]] and [[Instagram]] was launched. The official camping and project was launched on the 12th of November, 2019, the day after [[Remembrance Day]] and [[Veterans Day]] to help raise awareness of the project and of the international fighters and volunteers who were lost.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/The-Medal-for-the-Martyrs-102385111199884/|title=The Medal for the Martyrs - Facebook|last=|first=|date=12 November 2019|website=Facebook|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Funding ====\nOn 10 December 2019 a [[GoFundMe]] camping was started to raise funds for the project. The campaign was promoted through the Facebook page and Instagram account. The campaign has been unsuccessfully with only raising $490 [[Australian dollar|AUD]] to date.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.the-medal-for-the-martyrs|title=The Medal for the Martyrs - GoFundMe|last=|first=|date=10 December 2019|website=GoFundMe|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 January 2020}}</ref> To deal with this it was decided that a small initial order of medal would be ordered and mostly payed for by one of the project organisers in Australia.\n\n==== First issue ====\nOn 31 of January, 2020 it was posted on both the Facebook page and Instagram account that the first order of medals have been placed and in production.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/102385111199884/photos/a.128980338540361/159489875489407/?type=3&theater|title=The Medal for the Martyrs Facebook post|last=|first=|date=31 January 2020|website=Facebook|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 January 2020}}</ref> on the 8 of April, 2020 It was announced on both the Facebook page and Instagram account the first issue of medals had been received and the first few were being sent out.\n\n== Design ==\n\nThe Medal for the Martyrs is constructed around a replica of a captured bronze 25 fals coin that was made and used by ISIL within [[ISIL territorial claims|territory under their control]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/jenanmoussa/status/881226717657956352|title=1/ #BREAK: I obtained a silver ISIS coin. This is 1st concrete evidence that ISIS indeed introduced own currency in areas of its control|last=Moussa|first=Jenan|date=1 July 2017|website=Twitter - Reporter Jenan Moussa|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|dead-url=}}</ref> The metal disc and suspension bar are made as one from a zine die cast and plated bronze with a brushed finish applied. A ribbon is threaded through the suspension bar with a brooch attached behind at the top.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe idea to use a captured coin for the medal was inspired by the Australian [[Battle of Cocos|Sydney Emden medal]] and the idea to reappropriate the ISIL coin came from the reappropriation of the [[Nazi Germany]] [[Iron Cross#World War II|1939 Iron Cross]] medal's ribbon for the Israeli [[Fighters against Nazis Medal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fighters_against_Nazis_Medal|title=Fighters against Nazis Medal|last=|first=|date=|website=Wikipedia|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|dead-url=}}</ref>\n\nIt was an intentional decision for the medal to replicate an ISIL 25 fals coin as many of these and other similar coins were taken and confiscated by fighters in areas that were liberated from ISIL. ISIL's name and motto from the obverse side were removed and replaced with the acronyms of the three main Kurdish forces and a motto. This was deliberately done to show the liberation of and destruction of ISIL's so-called \"[[caliphate]]\" as well as symbolising an attack on and eradication of their extremist and harmful ideology.\n\nThe medal was manufactured and assembled by Cash's Awards and Promotion Solutions located in [[Frankston, Victoria|Frankston]], [[Australia]]. \n[[File:ISIS_25_Ful\u00fbs_coin_obverse.jpg|thumb|The obverse side of the ISIL 25 fals coin that the medal's obverse design was modelled from.]]\n\n==== Obverse ====\nThe obverse of the medal is a replica of the obverse side of an ISIL 25 fals coin. The medal reads at the top \"YPG SDF YPJ\" representing the three main forces that the volunteers were part of. This top line also replaces the original Arabic on the coin that read \"\u0627\u0644\u062f\u0648\u0644\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\u064a\u0629\" (The Islamic State).<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://english.religion.info/2018/12/23/the-return-of-the-gold-dinar-an-analysis-of-the-islamic-state-coin-production/|title=The Return of the Gold Dinar \u2013 An analysis of the Islamic State coin production|last=Moos|first=Olivier|date=23 December 2018|website=Religioscope|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|dead-url=}}</ref> The bottom line reads in [[Kurdish languages|Kurdish]] a saying and motto \"\u015eEH\u00ceD NAMIRIN\" (Martyrs Never Die). The motto replaces ISIL's motto that was on the coin \"\u062e\u0644\u0627\u0641\u0629 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u0645\u0646\u0647\u0627\u062c \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0628\u0648\u0629\" (A caliphate upon prophetic methodology).<ref name=\":1\" /> The area around the text \"YPG SDF YPJ\" and \"\u015eEH\u00ceD NAMIRIN\" is slightly sunken into the surface of the medal to create the illusion that the new text has been overstruck on the original text, symbolising an eradication of ISIL and other hostile entities. In the centre is the coin's value (25 fals) \"\u0662\u0665 \u0641\u0644\u0633\u0627\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://en.numista.com/catalogue/pieces154096.html|title=25 Falsan (thin variety)|last=|first=|date=|website=Numista|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|dead-url=}}</ref> within a segmented circle. To the centre right is the coin's original weight (15 grams) \"\u0661\u0665 \u063a\u0631\u0627\u0645\";<ref name=\":0\" /> and to the centre left is the coin's original metal content \"\u0646\u062d\u0627\u0633\" (copper).<ref name=\":0\" /> The coin's denomination, weight and metal composition were kept on the medal to create the illusion that the medal was made using a coin. \n[[File:ISIS_25_Ful\u00fbs_coin_reverse.jpg|thumb|The reverse side of the ISIL 25 fals coin that the medal's reverse design was modelled from.]]\n\n==== Reverse ====\nThe reverse of the medal is a replica of the reverse side of an ISIL 25 fals coin. At the centre is the [[Islamic calligraphy]] of a [[Hadith]] and bellow is the [[Gregorian calendar|Gregorian]] year in Arabic text of the year that the medal was first issued in \"\u0662\u0660\u0662\u0660\" (2020); all surrounded by a pattern of interwoven curved lines. The Hadith reads in Arabic \"\u0623\u0641\u0636\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0635\u062f\u0642\u0629 \u062c\u0647\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0642\u0644\", which translates to in English as \"The best charity is the effort of the less wealthy\".<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOne of the reasons why this Hadith was placed on the coin by ISIL was to use Islamic teachings and beliefs to pursued the people under their control to donate these coins back towards their cause. The main reasons why it was decided to keep it on the medal was that it preaches the importance of charity which can be interpreted to preach how important it was for the recipients to volunteer themselves and ultimately pay the highest price for there acts of charity for the Kurdish, Syrian and Iraqi peoples.\n\n==== Ribbon ====\nThe ribbon in 32&nbsp;mm wide. At the centre is a 4mm red ([[Pantone#Pantone Color Matching System|Pantone]] 108) stripe flanked on either side by black (Pantone Black) stripes to symbolise the blood and loss of those that were killed. On either side of the central stripes are two 3mm light brown (Pantone 1205) stripes representing the sandy desert terrain of Syria. On the left is a 5mm yellow (Pantone Yellow) stripe flanked on both sides by 2mm green (Pantone 350) stripes, representing the flag of the YPG. On the right is a 5mm green (Pantone 350) stripe flanked on both sides by 2mm yellow (Pantone Yellow) stripes, representing the flag of the YPJ.\n\nYellow, red and green also makeup the tricolour [[Flag of North and East Syria]] which is used by the [[Movement for a Democratic Society]] (TEV-DEM), the political coalition that governs the [[Autonomous Administration of North and East Syria]] (NES) also known as [[Rojava]].\n\n==== Suspension bar ====\nOn the front facing side of the suspension bar is the boxed in text \"ROJAVA\", the Kurdish name of the semi-autonomous region of north-eastern Syria and the main region in which the recipients fought in. Connecting the suspension bar to the disc is a five-pointed star, the same that is used on many Kurdish flags such as those of the YPG and YPJ. The back side has the laser engraved name of the recipient.\n\n== Recipients ==\nThe following is a table detailing all the recipients of the medal.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ypg-international.org|title=YPG International|last=|first=|date=2019|website=YPG International|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|dead-url=}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+First Issue: April 2020\n!Name\n!Nom de guerre\n!Date and Place fo Birth\n!Date and Place of Death\n!Additional Comments\n|-\n|Reece Harding\n|Bagok Serhed\n|31 August 1991, Middle Swan, Western Australia, Australia\n|27 June 2015, Gir\u00easp\u00ee, Sil\u00fbk, Gund\u00ea Genter\u00ee\n|\n|-\n|John Robert Gallagher\n|Gaber Rojava\n|30 September 1983, Toronto, Canada\n|4 November 2015, Heseke, Al-Hol\n|\n|-\n|Jamie Bright\n|Gaber Amed\n|1971, Australia\n|25 May 2016, Sadaddi, Gund\u00ea Malha, Northern Syria\n|\n|-\n|Daniel Pascual\n|Heval Amor\n|29 May 1993, Barcelona, Espa\u00f1a\n|12 July 2016, Sant Antoni De Vilamajor, Espa\u00f1a\n|Passed after returning home.\n|-\n|Levi Jonathan Shirley\n|Ag\u00eer Servan\n|Nevada, United States\n|14 July 2016, Minbic, Northern Syria\n|\n|-\n|Dean Carl Evans\n|Givara Rojava\n|Reading, United Kingdom\n|21 July 2016, Minbic, Northern Syria\n|\n|-\n|Ryan Lock\n|Berxwedan G\u00eevara\n|26 June 1996, Chichester, United Kingdom\n|21 December 2016, Raqqa, Northern Syria\n|\n|-\n|Paolo Todd\n|Kawa Amed\n|Los Angeles, United States\n|15 January 2017, Raqqa, Northern Syria\n|\n|-\n|[[Robert Grodt]]\n|Demhat Goldman\n|February 1989, California, United States\n|6 July 2017, Raqqa, Northern Syria\n|\n|-\n|Luke Rutter\n|Soro Zinar\n|Birkenhead, United Kingdom\n|6 July 2017, Raqqa, Northern Syria\n|\n|-\n|Farid Medjahed\n|Sah\u00een Qer\u00e7ox\n|Marselles, France\n|6 October 2017, Deir al-Zour, North Eastern Syria\n|\n|-\n|[[Jac Holmes]]\n|Sores Amanos\n|18 January 1993, Pool, United Kingdom\n|23 October 2017, Raqqa, Syria\n|\n|-\n|[[Oliver Hall (YPG fighter)|Ollie Hall]]\n|Can\u015f\u00ear Zagros\n|28 October 1993, United Kingdom\n|25 November 2017, Raqqa, Northern Syria\n|Two medals were produced, one for each of Ollie's parents who are divorced. Each medal is named \"Olivier Hall\" followed by either \"1/2\" or \"2/2\".\n|-\n|Sjoerd Heeger\n|Baran Sason\n|1993, Helmond, Netherlands\n|12 February 2018, Afrin, Rojava\n|\n|-\n|Kevin Howard\n|\n|23 September 1988, Grants Pass, Oregon, United States\n|30 March 2019, Tucson, Arizona, United States\n|Passed after returning home.\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" |An additional medal were produced with \"SPECIMEN\" laser engraved on the back of the suspension bar.\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Foreign fighters in the Syrian and Iraqi Civil Wars]]\n* [[International Freedom Battalion]]\n* [[List of military awards and decorations of the international military intervention against ISIL]]\n* [[Rojava conflict]]\n* [[Syrian Civil War]]\n* [[Syrian Kurdish\u2013Islamist conflict (2013\u2013present)]]\n* [[YPG International]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n{{Phaleristics}}\n\n<!--     CATEGORIES     -->\n[[Category:Awards honoring women| ]]\n[[Category:Martyrdom]]\n[[Category:Martyrs' monuments and memorials|*01]]\n[[Category:Martyrs]]\n[[Category:Posthumous recognitions]]\n[[Category:Wound decorations]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Medal_for_the_Martyrs"}
{"title_page": "Tom Malinowski", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Tom Malinowski\n|image        = Tom Malinowski, official portrait, 116th congress.jpg\n|state        = [[New Jersey]]\n|district     = {{ushr|NJ|7|7th}}\n|term_start   = January 3, 2019\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Leonard Lance]]\n|successor    = \n|office1      = [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]]\n|president1   = [[Barack Obama]]\n|deputy1      = [[Virginia L. Bennett]]\n|term_start1  = April 3, 2014\n|term_end1    = January 20, 2017\n|predecessor1 = [[Michael Posner (lawyer)|Michael Posner]]\n|successor1   = [[Robert Destro]]\n|birth_date   = {{nowrap|{{birth date and age|1965|9|23}}}}\n|birth_place  = [[S\u0142upsk]], [[Poland]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|education    = [[University of California, Berkeley]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[St Antony's College, Oxford]] ([[Master of Philosophy|MPhil]])\n|website      = {{url|malinowski.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Tom P. Malinowski''' (born September 23, 1965)<ref name=\"AllGov\"/> is an  [[United States|American]] politician and diplomat who is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[New Jersey's 7th congressional district]]. A [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], he previously served as [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]] in the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]]. Malinowski was first elected in [[2018 United States House of Representatives elections|2018]], defeating [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] incumbent [[Leonard Lance]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Malinowski Declares|url=https://www.insidernj.com/press-release/tom-malinowski-declares-candidacy-7th-congressional-district/|publisher=InsiderNJ|date=October 2, 2017|accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=New Jersey Primary Election Results |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/06/05/us/elections/results-new-jersey-primary-elections.html |accessdate=8 August 2018 |publisher=New York Times |date=June 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nMalinowski was born in [[S\u0142upsk]], Poland, and lived in [[Brwin\u00f3w]] until he left the country at the age of six with his mother, Joanna, who married [[Blair Clark]]. He was raised in [[Princeton, New Jersey]], and graduated from [[Princeton High School (New Jersey)|Princeton High School]] in 1983, where he wrote for the school newspaper ''The Tower'' and was an intern in the office of Senator [[Bill Bradley]].<ref name=\"AllGov\">{{cite web|title=Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor: Who Is Tom Malinowski?|url=http://www.allgov.com/news/appointments-and-resignations/assistant-secretary-of-state-for-democracy-human-rights-and-labor-who-is-tom-malinowski-130721?news=850617|publisher=AllGov|date=July 21, 2013|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> Malinowski received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[political science]] from the [[University of California, Berkeley]], in 1987 and a [[Master of Philosophy]] from [[St Antony's College, Oxford]], in 1991, where he was a [[Rhodes Scholar]].<ref name=\"AllGov\"/><ref name=\"State\">{{cite web|title=Tom Malinowski|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/ei/biog/224368.htm|publisher=[[U.S. Department of State]]|date=April 3, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early political career==\nMalinowski began his government career as a special assistant for Senator [[Daniel Patrick Moynihan]] in 1988. After attending Oxford, Malinowski worked for the [[Institute for Human Sciences]] in [[Vienna]], [[Austria]], and later as a research assistant for the [[Ford Foundation]] in 1993.<ref name=\"State\"/> From 1994 to 1998, Malinowski was a speechwriter for secretaries of state [[Warren Christopher]] and [[Madeleine Albright]], as well as a member of the [[Policy Planning Staff (United States)|Policy Planning Staff]] at the [[United States Department of State|Department of State]].<ref name=\"OpenSecrets\"/> From 1998 to 2001, Malinowski served as senior director on the [[United States National Security Council|National Security Council]] at the [[White House]], where he oversaw the drafting of President [[Bill Clinton]]'s foreign policy speeches and [[strategic communications]] efforts around the world.<ref name=\"State\"/><ref name=\"OpenSecrets\"/>\n\n==Human Rights Watch==\nFrom 2001 to 2013, Malinowski was a lobbyist for [[Human Rights Watch]].<ref name=\"State\"/><ref name=\"OpenSecrets\">{{cite web|title=Malinowski, Tom|url=http://www.opensecrets.org/revolving/rev_summary.php?id=78011|publisher=[[Center for Responsive Politics]]|date=April 3, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref name=twsPolitico0099/> Malinowski also opposed the United States supplying the Israeli Defense Forces with cluster munitions and asked then-Senator [[Hillary Clinton]] to not support Israel\u2019s construction of an \u2018illegal\u2019 wall in the West Bank.<ref>{{cite news |last1= |first1= |title=Human Rights Watch Lobbying Activity|url=https://freebeacon.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Screen-Shot-2018-07-20-at-3.00.16-PM.png |accessdate=22 March 2020 |publisher=Human Rights Watch}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Malinowski |first1=Tom |title=Human Rights watch Lobbying Activity|url=https://freebeacon.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Screen-Shot-2018-07-20-at-3.04.26-PM.png |accessdate=22 March 2020 |publisher=Human Rights Watch}}</ref>\n\n== Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor ==\nMalinowski was seen by some<ref name=\"Wapo3\">{{cite web|title=Nonprofit Groups Seeking Exceptions to Lobby Rule|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/21/us/politics/21lobby.html|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|date=April 20, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Wapo4\">{{cite web|title=The Good Lobbyist|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/23/opinion/23thu3.html?mcubz=2|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|date=April 22, 2006}}</ref> as a likely nominee for [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]] but his previous registration as a lobbyist while at Human Rights Watch necessitated a waiver from the President. On July 8, 2013, during President Obama's second term, Malinowski was nominated to serve as [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]].<ref>{{cite web|title=President Obama Announces More Key Administration Posts|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2013/07/08/president-obama-announces-more-key-administration-posts|publisher=[[White House]]|date=July 8, 2013|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=White House hires lobbyist Malinowski|last=Heil|first=Emily|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/in-the-loop/post/white-house-taps-tom-malinowski-for-human-rights-post/2013/07/09/1395416e-e8a3-11e2-a301-ea5a8116d211_blog.html|work=[[Washington Post]]|date=July 9, 2013|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> Malinowski testified before the [[Senate Foreign Relations Committee]] on September 24, 2013<ref>{{cite web|title=Statement for the Record by Tom Malinowski, Nominee for Assistant Secretary of State|url=http://www.foreign.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/Malinowski.pdf|publisher=[[United States Senate]]|date=September 24, 2013|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> and was confirmed by the [[U.S. Senate]] on April 2, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Senate confirms State Dept. nominee|url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2014/04/09/senate-confirms-state-dept-nominee/|work=[[Washington Blade]]|date=April 9, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Senate Confirms Tom Malinowski as New Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor|url=http://www.humanrightsfirst.org/press-release/senate-confirms-tom-malinowski-new-assistant-secretary-state-democracy-human-rights|publisher=[[Human Rights First]]|date=April 2, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Malinowski confirmed at DRL|url=http://www.demdigest.net/malinowski-confirmed-drl/|publisher=Democracy Digest|date=April 4, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> According to columnist [[Jennifer Rubin (journalist)|Jennifer Rubin]], Malinowski was praised in 2014 by leaders from both parties for his defense of human rights and his work toward ending torture.<ref name=twsWashPost040>Washington Post, Jennifer Rubin, February 21, 2014, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/right-turn/wp/2014/02/21/free-tom-malinowksi/ Free Tom Malinowski], Retrieved May 23, 2018, \"...Tom is widely respected for the indispensable role he has played in defense of human rights and fundamental freedoms, from ending torture to advancing democracy ... He received wide support from Democrats and Republicans who have been united in their criticism of the administration\u2019s ... attitude toward human rights....</ref>\n\nWhile working in the State Department, Malinowski spearheaded efforts to assist persecuted religious minorities targeted by [[ISIS]] in [[Iraq]].<ref>{{cite web|title=A/S Malinowski Briefs Congressional Leaders on ISIL\u2019s Persecution of Religious Minorities in Iraq and Syria=|url=https://geneva.usmission.gov/2014/09/12/as-malinowski-briefs-congressional-leaders-on-isils-persecution-of-religious-minorities-in-iraq-and-syria/|publisher=United States of America Geneva Mission|date=September 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Malinowski Testimony|url=https://www.foreign.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/Malinowski_Testimony.pdf|publisher=[[U.S. Senate]]|date=December 9, 2014}}</ref> He also oversaw efforts to sanction [[North Korea]]n officials for human rights abuses and increase the flow of uncensored information into the country.<ref>{{cite web|title=U.S. compiling list of North Korea human rights violators|url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2016/04/27/US-compiling-list-of-North-Korea-human-rights-violators/8071461768502/|publisher=[[UPI]]|date=April 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sanctions on N.K. leader 'just the start,' more blacklisting to come: senior U.S. diplomat|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/northkorea/2016/07/08/0401000000AEN20160708001200315.html| publisher=[[Yonhap]]|date=July 8, 2016}}</ref> He led State Department efforts to defend the [[LGBT]] community around the world and oversaw the appointment of the first [[Randy W. Berry|Special Envoy for LGBT rights]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Support for Gay Rights in Africa|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/29/opinion/support-for-gay-rights-in-africa.html?mcubz=1&mtrref=undefined&assetType=opinion|publisher=|date=December 29, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to the Special Envoy for LGBT Rights|url=http://www.hrc.org/blog/welcome-to-the-special-envoy-for-lgbt-rights|publisher=[[Human Rights Campaign]]|date=February 27, 2015}}</ref> Malinowski backed [[United Nations]]' efforts to investigate possible [[Alleged war crimes during the final stages of the Sri Lankan Civil War|war crimes]] committed during the [[Sri Lankan Civil War]].<ref>{{cite web|title=U.S. to Support Sri Lanka Plan to Investigate War Crimes|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/27/world/asia/united-states-supports-sri-lanka-investigation-of-war-crimes.html?mtrref=undefined|publisher=[[NY Times]]|date=August 26, 2015}}</ref> He also worked on decreasing civilian casualties from US military operations in the [[Middle East]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Obama\u2019s New Executive Order Increases Drone Transparency, Official Says|url=https://www.washingtonreport.me/2016-august/september/obamas-new-executive-order-increases-drone-transparency-official-says.html|publisher=[[Washington Report on Middle East Affairs]]|date=August 2016}}</ref> and assisted with sanctioning Russian officials for [[Magnitsky Act|human rights abuses]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Five Russians blacklisted for alleged human rights abuses|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/five-russians-blacklisted-for-human-rights-abuses/2017/01/09/1b00068c-d6b6-11e6-9f9f-5cdb4b7f8dd7_story.html|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|date=January 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Malinowski and Omar in 2019.png|thumb|Malinowski with [[Ilhan Omar]] in [[Washington DC]], 2019]]\nIn July 2014, Malinowski was [[persona non grata|expelled]] by [[Bahrain]]'s [[Government of Bahrain|government]] after meeting with members of an opposition group in the course of a scheduled visit.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|title=US diplomat Tom Malinowski expelled from Bahrain|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-28204511|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=July 7, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bahrain: U.S. diplomat 'unwelcome and should immediately leave'|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/07/08/world/meast/bahrain-us-diplomat-unwelcome/|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=July 8, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bahrain expels top US diplomat after meeting with main opposition group|url=https://www.rt.com/news/171084-bahrain-expels-us-diplomat/|publisher=[[RT (TV network)|RT]]|date=July 7, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> The foreign ministry of Bahrain argued that Malinowski's meeting improperly intervened in the country's affairs but noted the incident would not affect [[Bahrain\u2013United States relations]].<ref name=\"BBC\"/> The [[U.S. State Department]] released a statement of concern about the actions while [[United States Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] [[John Kerry]] called Bahrain's actions unacceptable and contrary to diplomatic protocol.<ref name=\"BBC\"/><ref name=\"WSJ\">{{cite web|last=Schwartz|first=Felicia|title=Tension Between Bahrain and U.S. Continues Over Diplomat's Expulsion|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/tension-between-bahrain-and-u-s-continues-over-diplomats-expulsion-1405387624|work=[[Wall Street Journal]]|date=July 14, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Statement on the Decision by the Government of Bahrain To Find Assistant Secretary Malinowski Persona Non Grata and To Expel Him From Bahrain|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2014/07/228839.htm|publisher=[[U.S. Department of State]]|date=July 7, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> Malinowski returned to the country in December 2014 with the [[Anne W. Patterson|assistant secretary of state for Near Eastern affairs]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Gordon|first=Michael|title=Expelled U.S. Official to Return to Bahrain|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/03/world/middleeast/bahrain-us-human-rights-official-tom-malinowski.html?_r=0|work=[[New York Times]]|date=December 3, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Press Availability with A/S Tom Malinowski and A/S Anne Patterson|url=http://bahrain.usembassy.gov/pas-120414.html|publisher=[[U.S. Department of State]]|date=December 4, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414204305/http://bahrain.usembassy.gov/pas-120414.html|archivedate=April 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the end of his tenure at the State Department, Malinowski joined fellow former Obama officials to lobby Congress in an effort to prevent the [[Trump Administration]] from lifting the [[International sanctions during the Ukrainian crisis|sanctions]] on [[Russia]] following its [[Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)|invasion of Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Former Diplomats: Trump Team Sought to Lift Sanctions on Russia|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/politics/white-house/former-diplomats-trump-team-sought-lift-sanctions-russia-n767406|publisher=[[NBC News]]|date=June 1, 2017}}</ref> He criticized [[Donald Trump]] for having an \"obscene fondness\" for the world's tyrants and for instituting a \"complete departure from decades of American tradition.\"<ref name=twsPolitico0099>Politico magazine, Susan B. Glasser, June 19, 2017, [https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/06/19/tom-malinowski-man-who-argued-with-dictators-215278 The Man Who Argued With Dictators: Tom Malinowski spent years trying to get President Obama to care more about human rights. Now, he\u2019s figuring out what to do with a president who doesn\u2019t seem to care at all.], Retrieved May 24, 2018, \"...Malinowski spent the past few years pushing Obama from the inside on human rights ... former Washington director of Human Rights Watch ... leading the resistance from the outside to Trump and what he calls his \u201cobscene\u201d fondness for the world\u2019s tyrants....\"</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\nOn October 2, 2017, Malinowski announced his candidacy for U.S. Congress in [[New Jersey's 7th congressional district]] in the [[2018 United States elections|2018 midterm elections]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kamisar|first1=Ben|title=Obama State Department official to run for House in NJ|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/353408-obama-state-department-official-to-run-for-house-in-nj|accessdate=16 May 2018|publisher=The Hill|date=October 2, 2017}}</ref> He decided to run for Congress after the [[2016 United States presidential election|November 2016 election of Donald Trump]], which he saw as an indication that America was in \"deep trouble.\"<ref name=twsBloomberg445>Albert R. Hunt, May 2, 2018, Bloomberg News, [https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2018-05-02/democratic-house-candidates-look-mighty-familiar Some Democratic Candidates Look Mighty Familiar], Retrieved May 15, 2018, \"... Malinowski, an assistant secretary of State for President Obama and a State Department official under Clinton ... America, he believes, \"is in deep trouble.\"...\"</ref> Malinowski said he decided to run for office because of what he called the Trump administration's \"effort to take down the Affordable Care Act with no viable replacement. It was the Muslim ban, and attacks on immigrants, it was the tearing up of alliances and commitments internationally. It was the taking down of environmental protections, it was refusing to invest in infrastructure.\"<ref name=\"twsNBCWash11\">May 27, 2018, NBC News Washington (Channel 4), [https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/politics/Former-Obama-Staffers-Elections-483805841.html Fired Up by Trump, Dozens of Former Obama Staffers Run for Office: The surge of Democratic candidates with ties to Obama has the potential to fill state and federal legislatures with like-minded allies], Retrieved May 30, 2018, \"...it was the effort to take down the Affordable Care Act with no viable replacement...\"</ref>\n\nMalinowski supports the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|Affordable Care Act]] and criticized the Republican Party for \"whittling away at the Affordable Care Act year after year.\"<ref name=twsInsiderNJ44>Insider New Jersey, May 12, 2018, Staff writer, [https://www.insidernj.com/cd7-democratic-challenger-malinowski-formally-opens-main-headquarters-pallone/ CD7 Democratic Challenger Malinowski Formally Opens his Main Headquarters with Pallone], Retrieved May 14, 2018, \"... He\u2019ll fight to protect the Affordable Care Act.....\"</ref>  He supports raising the minimum wage to $15 per hour as well as enhanced collective bargaining rights and protections for workers.<ref name=twsNJGlobe11/>  Malinowski sees the Democratic Party, in contrast to the GOP, as promoting fiscal responsibility, law enforcement, family values, and patriotism.<ref name=\"twsWashPost0786\">E. J. Dionne, July 15, 2018, Washington Post, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/does-the-blue-wave-start-in-jersey/2018/07/15/db44a0b2-86e4-11e8-8f6c-46cb43e3f306_story.html?wpisrc=nl_headlines&wpmm=1 Does the blue wave start in Jersey?], Retrieved July 16, 2018</ref>\n\n[[File:Candidate for Congress NJ-7th Tom Malinowski at campaign headquarters speaking with a voter.jpg|thumb|upright|Malinowski at his campaign headquarters in [[Martinsville, New Jersey]]]]\nHis endorsements included the Hunterdon County Democratic Committee<ref name=\"twsNJHills41\">April 27, 2018, New Jersey Hills, [http://www.newjerseyhills.com/hunterdon_review/news/first-lady-tammy-murphy-to-speak-at-county-democratic-brunch/article_a25ed6e9-39ca-56e0-a286-f38ca8e86f59.html First Lady Tammy Murphy to speak at county Democratic brunch on Sunday, April 29], Retrieved May 15, 2018, \"...Tom Malinowski ... endorsed by the HCDC ...\"</ref> and the [[Communications Workers of America]].<ref name=\"twsNJGlobe11\">David Wildstein, April 23, 2018, New Jersey Globe, [https://newjerseyglobe.com/congress/cwa-endorses-malinowski/ CWA Endorses Malinowski], Retrieved May 15, 2018</ref> On June 5, 2018, he faced social worker Peter Jacob and lawyer Goutam Jois.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Jersey's 7th Congressional District election, 2018|url=https://ballotpedia.org/New_Jersey%27s_7th_Congressional_District_election,_2018|accessdate=8 May 2018|publisher=Ballotpedia}}</ref> He defeated Jacob and Jois, receiving 66.8% of the vote and winning all counties in the district<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/new-jersey-house-district-7-primary-election|title=New Jersey Primary Election Results: Seventh House District|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.njelections.org/assets/pdf/election-results/2018/2018-official-primary-results-us-house.pdf|title=Candidates for House of Representatives For PRIMARY ELECTION 06/05/2018 Election,|last=|first=|date=July 20, 2018|website=|access-date=}}</ref> Malinowski went onto to defeat incumbent Republican [[Leonard Lance]].\n\nMalinowski criticized Lance, saying he \"shifted to the right when he was scared of the [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party]] and he's moving to the left when he's scared of his increasingly moderate and energized constituents.\"<ref name=\"twsNJcom441\">Jonathan D. Salant, May 14, 2018, NJ.com, [http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2018/05/how_njs_most_endangered_congressman_is_trying_to_w.html This N.J. Republican is in big trouble because of Trump. Here's what he's doing about it.], Retrieved May 15, 2018</ref> On November 6, Malinowski won the election, receiving 51.7% of the vote. While Malinowski and Lance each carried three of the six counties in the district, Malinowski won the district's shares of Somerset and Union counties by a combined 22,300 votes, more than the overall margin of 16,200 votes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/new-jersey-house-district-7|title=New Jersey\u2019s Seventh House District Election Results: Tom Malinowski vs. Leonard Lance|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.njelections.org/assets/pdf/election-results/2018/2018-official-general-election-results-us-house.pdf|title=Official List Candidates for House of Representatives For GENERAL ELECTION 11/06/2018 Election|last=|first=|date=December 3, 2018|website=|access-date=}}</ref> When he took office in January 2019, he became the first Democrat to represent the 7th and its predecessors since 1961.\n\nOn February 26, 2020, Malinowski stated that he would \u201cabsolutely\u201d support [[Bernie Sanders]] if he were the Democratic Presidential nominee.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mascaro |first1=Lisa |title=Pelosi urges Democratic unity amid Sanders\u2019 campaign surge |url=https://apnews.com/7ef003d3d777ba44bb4e24fed66809f8 |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=The Associated Press |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Committee assignments ===\n\n* [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|'''Committee on Foreign Affairs''']]\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Middle East, North Africa and International Terrorism|Subcommittee on the Middle East, North Africa and International Terrorism]]\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n* [[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|'''Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure''']]\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Highways and Transit|Subcommittee on Highways and Transit]]\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials|Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials]]\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment|Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment]]\n\n=== Caucus memberships ===\n* '''[[LGBT Equality Caucus]]'''\n* '''[[New Democrat Coalition]]'''\n* '''End Corruption Caucus'''<ref name=\"Malinowski Press Release 2020.01.21\">{{cite web |title=Representative Malinowski Leads Fight To End Corruption in Washington |url=https://malinowski.house.gov/media/press-releases/representative-malinowski-leads-fight-end-corruption-washington |website=Tom Malinowski Congressional Web Site |accessdate=27 January 2020 |date=21 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Congressman Max Rose Press Release 2020.01.16\">{{cite web |title=10 Years After Disastrous Citizens United Decision, Rose, Porter, Freshmen Dems Launch New \u2018End Corruption\u2019 Caucus |url=https://maxrose.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=2450 |website=Max Rose Congressional Web Site |accessdate=27 January 2020 |date=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n===Illegal Immigrants===\nAt an August 2019 town hall, Malinowski told constituents that illegal immigrants are needed to mow \"our beautiful lawns\" and perform menial jobs rejected by tech-focused teenagers.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ferrechio |first1=Susan |title=Democratic lawmaker: Illegal immigrants needed to mow 'our beautiful lawns' |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/congress/democratic-lawmaker-illegal-immigrants-needed-to-mow-our-beautiful-lawns |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=Washington Examiner |date=August 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Wulfsohn |first1=Joseph |title=Dem Rep. Tom Malinowski: We need illegal immigrants to 'mow our beautiful lawns' |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/dem-rep-tom-malinowski-illegal-immigrants-to-mow-lawns |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=Fox News |date=August 22, 2019}}</ref> The comments made national headlines and drew backlash from critics who called Malinowski \"out of touch\". Questions were raised as to whether Malinowski pays illegal immigrants to mow his personal lawn.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moritz-Rabson |first1=Daniel |title=DEMOCRATIC CONGRESSMAN SAYS UNDOCUMENTED IMMIGRANTS ARE GOOD FOR 'MOWING OUR BEAUTIFUL LAWNS' |url=https://www.newsweek.com/democratic-congressman-says-undocumented-immigrants-are-good-mowing-our-beautiful-lawns-1455893 |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=Newsweek |date=August 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Prince |first1=Molly |title=WATCH: Dem Lawmaker Says Illegal Immigrants Are Needed To Mow \u2018Our Beautiful Lawns\u2019 |url=https://www.dailywire.com/news/watch-dem-lawmaker-says-illegal-immigrants-are-molly-prince |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=The Daily Wire |date=August 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Meads |first1=Timothy |title=WATCH: Dem Lawmaker Says Illegal Immigrants Are Needed To Mow \u2018Our Beautiful Lawns\u2019 |url=New Jersey Democrat: We Need Illegals To Mow Our 'Beautiful Lawns'e |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=Townhall |date=August 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Impeachment===\nMalinowski was the first member of the New Jersey congressional delegation to call to begin the impeachment inquiry of President [[Donald Trump]] in May 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moran |first1=Tom |title=Malinowski, the first Jersey House member to favor impeachment hearings, explains why|url=https://www.nj.com/opinion/2019/05/malinowski-the-first-jersey-house-member-to-favor-impeachment-hearings-explains-why-moran.html |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=NJ.com |date=May 29, 2019}}</ref> The decision was criticized by Republican operatives.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Biryukov |first1=Nikita |title=Malinowski backs start of impeachment inquiry |url=https://newjerseyglobe.com/congress/malinowski-backs-impeachment/ |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=New Jersey Globe |date=May 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMalinowski owns a home in [[Washington, D.C.]], and was registered to vote there as of March 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pizarro |first1=Max |title=Residency Question Hounds Malinowski on Eve of Union County Vote |url=https://www.insidernj.com/residency-question-hounds-malinowski-eve-union-county-vote/ |accessdate=16 July 2018 |publisher=InsiderNJ |date=March 6, 2018}}</ref> He began renting a home in [[Rocky Hill, New Jersey]], in September 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Brodesser-Akner |first1=Claude |title=What's really going on with all these 'carpetbagger' political attacks in New Jersey? |url=https://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2018/07/hed_whats_really_going_on_with_all_these_carpetbag.html |accessdate=17 July 2018 |publisher=NJ.com |date=July 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Pathe |first1=Simone |title=Could Past DC Residency Be Liability for Some Democrats? |url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/past-dc-residency-liability-democrats |accessdate=16 July 2018 |publisher=Roll Call |date=March 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMalinowski's stepfather [[Blair Clark]] was a journalist. Clark's sister was [[Anne Clark Martindell|Anne Martindell]], a member of the [[New Jersey State Senate]] (1974\u20131977) and a [[List of ambassadors of the United States to New Zealand|United States ambassador to New Zealand]] (1979\u20131981).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wildstein |first1=David |title=Malinowski and the residency thing |url=https://newjerseyglobe.com/section-2/malinowski-residency-thing/ |accessdate= August 8, 2018 |publisher=New Jersey Globe |date=March 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMalinowski has one daughter, Emily.<ref>{{cite news | last1=Muscavage |first1=Nick |title= NJ elections: Democrat Tom Malinowski unseats Republican Leonard Lance in NJ's 7th Congressional District  |url=https://www.mycentraljersey.com/story/news/politics/2018/11/07/nj-7th-district-congress-tom-malinowski-defeats-leonard-lance/1902521002/ |accessdate= March 3, 2020 |publisher= Courier News and Home News Tribune |date=November 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://malinowski.house.gov/ Congressman Tom Malinowski] official U.S. House website\n*[https://malinowskifornj.com/ Tom Malinowski for Congress]\n{{CongLinks|fec=H8NJ07223|votesmart=179645|congbio=M001203|congress=tom-malinowski/M001203}}\n\n{{Commons category|Tomasz P. Malinowski}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Michael Posner (lawyer)|Michael Posner]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]]|years=2014\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Virginia L. Bennett]]<br>{{small|Acting}}}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Leonard Lance]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from New Jersey|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[New Jersey's 7th congressional district]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Elaine Luria]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=383rd}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ben McAdams]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Members of the U.S. House of Representatives}}\n{{NJ-FedRep}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Malinowski, Tom}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Antony's College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:American Rhodes Scholars]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Human Rights Watch people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:New Jersey Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from Princeton, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Rocky Hill, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from S\u0142upsk]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Princeton High School (New Jersey) alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Assistant Secretaries of State]]\n[[Category:United States National Security Council staffers]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:Progressivism in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Tom Malinowski\n|image        = Tom Malinowski, official portrait, 116th congress.jpg\n|state        = [[New Jersey]]\n|district     = {{ushr|NJ|7|7th}}\n|term_start   = January 3, 2019\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Leonard Lance]]\n|successor    = \n|office1      = [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]]\n|president1   = [[Barack Obama]]\n|deputy1      = [[Virginia L. Bennett]]\n|term_start1  = April 3, 2014\n|term_end1    = January 20, 2017\n|predecessor1 = [[Michael Posner (lawyer)|Michael Posner]]\n|successor1   = [[Robert Destro]]\n|birth_date   = {{nowrap|{{birth date and age|1965|9|23}}}}\n|birth_place  = [[S\u0142upsk]], [[Poland]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|education    = [[University of California, Berkeley]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[St Antony's College, Oxford]] ([[Master of Philosophy|MPhil]])\n|website      = {{url|malinowski.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Tom P. Malinowski''' (born September 23, 1965)<ref name=\"AllGov\"/> is an  [[United States|American]] politician and diplomat who is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[New Jersey's 7th congressional district]]. A [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], he previously served as [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]] in the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]]. Malinowski was first elected in [[2018 United States House of Representatives elections|2018]], defeating [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] incumbent [[Leonard Lance]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Malinowski Declares|url=https://www.insidernj.com/press-release/tom-malinowski-declares-candidacy-7th-congressional-district/|publisher=InsiderNJ|date=October 2, 2017|accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=New Jersey Primary Election Results |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/06/05/us/elections/results-new-jersey-primary-elections.html |accessdate=8 August 2018 |publisher=New York Times |date=June 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nMalinowski was born in [[S\u0142upsk]], Poland, and lived in [[Brwin\u00f3w]] until he left the country at the age of six with his mother, Joanna, who married [[Blair Clark]]. He was raised in [[Princeton, New Jersey]], and graduated from [[Princeton High School (New Jersey)|Princeton High School]] in 1983, where he wrote for the school newspaper ''The Tower'' and was an intern in the office of Senator [[Bill Bradley]].<ref name=\"AllGov\">{{cite web|title=Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor: Who Is Tom Malinowski?|url=http://www.allgov.com/news/appointments-and-resignations/assistant-secretary-of-state-for-democracy-human-rights-and-labor-who-is-tom-malinowski-130721?news=850617|publisher=AllGov|date=July 21, 2013|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> Malinowski received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[political science]] from the [[University of California, Berkeley]], in 1987 and a [[Master of Philosophy]] from [[St Antony's College, Oxford]], in 1991, where he was a [[Rhodes Scholar]].<ref name=\"AllGov\"/><ref name=\"State\">{{cite web|title=Tom Malinowski|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/ei/biog/224368.htm|publisher=[[U.S. Department of State]]|date=April 3, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early political career==\nMalinowski began his government career as a special assistant for Senator [[Daniel Patrick Moynihan]] in 1988. After attending Oxford, Malinowski worked for the [[Institute for Human Sciences]] in [[Vienna]], [[Austria]], and later as a research assistant for the [[Ford Foundation]] in 1993.<ref name=\"State\"/> From 1994 to 1998, Malinowski was a speechwriter for secretaries of state [[Warren Christopher]] and [[Madeleine Albright]], as well as a member of the [[Policy Planning Staff (United States)|Policy Planning Staff]] at the [[United States Department of State|Department of State]].<ref name=\"OpenSecrets\"/> From 1998 to 2001, Malinowski served as senior director on the [[United States National Security Council|National Security Council]] at the [[White House]], where he oversaw the drafting of President [[Bill Clinton]]'s foreign policy speeches and [[strategic communications]] efforts around the world.<ref name=\"State\"/><ref name=\"OpenSecrets\"/>\n\n==Human Rights Watch==\nFrom 2001 to 2013, Malinowski was a lobbyist for [[Human Rights Watch]].<ref name=\"State\"/><ref name=\"OpenSecrets\">{{cite web|title=Malinowski, Tom|url=http://www.opensecrets.org/revolving/rev_summary.php?id=78011|publisher=[[Center for Responsive Politics]]|date=April 3, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref name=twsPolitico0099/> In this position, he advocated for terrorists' rights during the [[War on Terror]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Scher |first1=Brent |title=NJ Dem Tom Malinowski Tries and Fails to Defend Record of \u2018Lobbying for Terrorist Rights\u2019|url=https://freebeacon.com/politics/nj-dem-tom-malinowski-tries-fails-to-defend-record-of-lobbying-for-terrorist-rights/|publisher=[[The Washington Free Beacon]]|date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> Going as far as to say that [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp|Guantanamo Bay]] should be shut down.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Malinowski |first1=Tom |title=Four Good Reasons Why Guantanamo Should Be Closed|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2006/11/22/four-good-reasons-why-guantanamo-should-be-closed# |accessdate=22 March 2020 |publisher=Human Rights Watch |date=November 22, 2006}}</ref> Malinowski also campaigned against American support of the Israeli military. Malinowski opposed the United States supplying the Israeli Defense Forces with cluster munitions and asked then-Senator [[Hillary Clinton]] to not support Israel\u2019s construction of an \u2018illegal\u2019 wall in the West Bank.<ref>{{cite news |last1= |first1= |title=Human Rights Watch Lobbying Activity|url=https://freebeacon.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Screen-Shot-2018-07-20-at-3.00.16-PM.png |accessdate=22 March 2020 |publisher=Human Rights Watch}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Malinowski |first1=Tom |title=Human Rights watch Lobbying Activity|url=https://freebeacon.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Screen-Shot-2018-07-20-at-3.04.26-PM.png |accessdate=22 March 2020 |publisher=Human Rights Watch}}</ref>\n\n== Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor ==\nMalinowski was seen by some<ref name=\"Wapo3\">{{cite web|title=Nonprofit Groups Seeking Exceptions to Lobby Rule|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/21/us/politics/21lobby.html|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|date=April 20, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Wapo4\">{{cite web|title=The Good Lobbyist|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/23/opinion/23thu3.html?mcubz=2|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|date=April 22, 2006}}</ref> as a likely nominee for [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]] but his previous registration as a lobbyist while at Human Rights Watch necessitated a waiver from the President. On July 8, 2013, during President Obama's second term, Malinowski was nominated to serve as [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]].<ref>{{cite web|title=President Obama Announces More Key Administration Posts|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2013/07/08/president-obama-announces-more-key-administration-posts|publisher=[[White House]]|date=July 8, 2013|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=White House hires lobbyist Malinowski|last=Heil|first=Emily|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/in-the-loop/post/white-house-taps-tom-malinowski-for-human-rights-post/2013/07/09/1395416e-e8a3-11e2-a301-ea5a8116d211_blog.html|work=[[Washington Post]]|date=July 9, 2013|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> Malinowski testified before the [[Senate Foreign Relations Committee]] on September 24, 2013<ref>{{cite web|title=Statement for the Record by Tom Malinowski, Nominee for Assistant Secretary of State|url=http://www.foreign.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/Malinowski.pdf|publisher=[[United States Senate]]|date=September 24, 2013|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> and was confirmed by the [[U.S. Senate]] on April 2, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Senate confirms State Dept. nominee|url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2014/04/09/senate-confirms-state-dept-nominee/|work=[[Washington Blade]]|date=April 9, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Senate Confirms Tom Malinowski as New Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor|url=http://www.humanrightsfirst.org/press-release/senate-confirms-tom-malinowski-new-assistant-secretary-state-democracy-human-rights|publisher=[[Human Rights First]]|date=April 2, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Malinowski confirmed at DRL|url=http://www.demdigest.net/malinowski-confirmed-drl/|publisher=Democracy Digest|date=April 4, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> According to columnist [[Jennifer Rubin (journalist)|Jennifer Rubin]], Malinowski was praised in 2014 by leaders from both parties for his defense of human rights and his work toward ending torture.<ref name=twsWashPost040>Washington Post, Jennifer Rubin, February 21, 2014, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/right-turn/wp/2014/02/21/free-tom-malinowksi/ Free Tom Malinowski], Retrieved May 23, 2018, \"...Tom is widely respected for the indispensable role he has played in defense of human rights and fundamental freedoms, from ending torture to advancing democracy ... He received wide support from Democrats and Republicans who have been united in their criticism of the administration\u2019s ... attitude toward human rights....</ref>\n\nWhile working in the State Department, Malinowski spearheaded efforts to assist persecuted religious minorities targeted by [[ISIS]] in [[Iraq]].<ref>{{cite web|title=A/S Malinowski Briefs Congressional Leaders on ISIL\u2019s Persecution of Religious Minorities in Iraq and Syria=|url=https://geneva.usmission.gov/2014/09/12/as-malinowski-briefs-congressional-leaders-on-isils-persecution-of-religious-minorities-in-iraq-and-syria/|publisher=United States of America Geneva Mission|date=September 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Malinowski Testimony|url=https://www.foreign.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/Malinowski_Testimony.pdf|publisher=[[U.S. Senate]]|date=December 9, 2014}}</ref> He also oversaw efforts to sanction [[North Korea]]n officials for human rights abuses and increase the flow of uncensored information into the country.<ref>{{cite web|title=U.S. compiling list of North Korea human rights violators|url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2016/04/27/US-compiling-list-of-North-Korea-human-rights-violators/8071461768502/|publisher=[[UPI]]|date=April 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sanctions on N.K. leader 'just the start,' more blacklisting to come: senior U.S. diplomat|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/northkorea/2016/07/08/0401000000AEN20160708001200315.html| publisher=[[Yonhap]]|date=July 8, 2016}}</ref> He led State Department efforts to defend the [[LGBT]] community around the world and oversaw the appointment of the first [[Randy W. Berry|Special Envoy for LGBT rights]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Support for Gay Rights in Africa|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/29/opinion/support-for-gay-rights-in-africa.html?mcubz=1&mtrref=undefined&assetType=opinion|publisher=|date=December 29, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to the Special Envoy for LGBT Rights|url=http://www.hrc.org/blog/welcome-to-the-special-envoy-for-lgbt-rights|publisher=[[Human Rights Campaign]]|date=February 27, 2015}}</ref> Malinowski backed [[United Nations]]' efforts to investigate possible [[Alleged war crimes during the final stages of the Sri Lankan Civil War|war crimes]] committed during the [[Sri Lankan Civil War]].<ref>{{cite web|title=U.S. to Support Sri Lanka Plan to Investigate War Crimes|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/27/world/asia/united-states-supports-sri-lanka-investigation-of-war-crimes.html?mtrref=undefined|publisher=[[NY Times]]|date=August 26, 2015}}</ref> He also worked on decreasing civilian casualties from US military operations in the [[Middle East]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Obama\u2019s New Executive Order Increases Drone Transparency, Official Says|url=https://www.washingtonreport.me/2016-august/september/obamas-new-executive-order-increases-drone-transparency-official-says.html|publisher=[[Washington Report on Middle East Affairs]]|date=August 2016}}</ref> and assisted with sanctioning Russian officials for [[Magnitsky Act|human rights abuses]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Five Russians blacklisted for alleged human rights abuses|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/five-russians-blacklisted-for-human-rights-abuses/2017/01/09/1b00068c-d6b6-11e6-9f9f-5cdb4b7f8dd7_story.html|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|date=January 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Malinowski and Omar in 2019.png|thumb|Malinowski with [[Ilhan Omar]] in [[Washington DC]], 2019]]\nIn July 2014, Malinowski was [[persona non grata|expelled]] by [[Bahrain]]'s [[Government of Bahrain|government]] after meeting with members of an opposition group in the course of a scheduled visit.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|title=US diplomat Tom Malinowski expelled from Bahrain|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-28204511|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=July 7, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bahrain: U.S. diplomat 'unwelcome and should immediately leave'|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/07/08/world/meast/bahrain-us-diplomat-unwelcome/|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=July 8, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bahrain expels top US diplomat after meeting with main opposition group|url=https://www.rt.com/news/171084-bahrain-expels-us-diplomat/|publisher=[[RT (TV network)|RT]]|date=July 7, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> The foreign ministry of Bahrain argued that Malinowski's meeting improperly intervened in the country's affairs but noted the incident would not affect [[Bahrain\u2013United States relations]].<ref name=\"BBC\"/> The [[U.S. State Department]] released a statement of concern about the actions while [[United States Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] [[John Kerry]] called Bahrain's actions unacceptable and contrary to diplomatic protocol.<ref name=\"BBC\"/><ref name=\"WSJ\">{{cite web|last=Schwartz|first=Felicia|title=Tension Between Bahrain and U.S. Continues Over Diplomat's Expulsion|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/tension-between-bahrain-and-u-s-continues-over-diplomats-expulsion-1405387624|work=[[Wall Street Journal]]|date=July 14, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Statement on the Decision by the Government of Bahrain To Find Assistant Secretary Malinowski Persona Non Grata and To Expel Him From Bahrain|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2014/07/228839.htm|publisher=[[U.S. Department of State]]|date=July 7, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> Malinowski returned to the country in December 2014 with the [[Anne W. Patterson|assistant secretary of state for Near Eastern affairs]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Gordon|first=Michael|title=Expelled U.S. Official to Return to Bahrain|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/03/world/middleeast/bahrain-us-human-rights-official-tom-malinowski.html?_r=0|work=[[New York Times]]|date=December 3, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Press Availability with A/S Tom Malinowski and A/S Anne Patterson|url=http://bahrain.usembassy.gov/pas-120414.html|publisher=[[U.S. Department of State]]|date=December 4, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414204305/http://bahrain.usembassy.gov/pas-120414.html|archivedate=April 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the end of his tenure at the State Department, Malinowski joined fellow former Obama officials to lobby Congress in an effort to prevent the [[Trump Administration]] from lifting the [[International sanctions during the Ukrainian crisis|sanctions]] on [[Russia]] following its [[Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)|invasion of Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Former Diplomats: Trump Team Sought to Lift Sanctions on Russia|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/politics/white-house/former-diplomats-trump-team-sought-lift-sanctions-russia-n767406|publisher=[[NBC News]]|date=June 1, 2017}}</ref> He criticized [[Donald Trump]] for having an \"obscene fondness\" for the world's tyrants and for instituting a \"complete departure from decades of American tradition.\"<ref name=twsPolitico0099>Politico magazine, Susan B. Glasser, June 19, 2017, [https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/06/19/tom-malinowski-man-who-argued-with-dictators-215278 The Man Who Argued With Dictators: Tom Malinowski spent years trying to get President Obama to care more about human rights. Now, he\u2019s figuring out what to do with a president who doesn\u2019t seem to care at all.], Retrieved May 24, 2018, \"...Malinowski spent the past few years pushing Obama from the inside on human rights ... former Washington director of Human Rights Watch ... leading the resistance from the outside to Trump and what he calls his \u201cobscene\u201d fondness for the world\u2019s tyrants....\"</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\nOn October 2, 2017, Malinowski announced his candidacy for U.S. Congress in [[New Jersey's 7th congressional district]] in the [[2018 United States elections|2018 midterm elections]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kamisar|first1=Ben|title=Obama State Department official to run for House in NJ|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/353408-obama-state-department-official-to-run-for-house-in-nj|accessdate=16 May 2018|publisher=The Hill|date=October 2, 2017}}</ref> He decided to run for Congress after the [[2016 United States presidential election|November 2016 election of Donald Trump]], which he saw as an indication that America was in \"deep trouble.\"<ref name=twsBloomberg445>Albert R. Hunt, May 2, 2018, Bloomberg News, [https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2018-05-02/democratic-house-candidates-look-mighty-familiar Some Democratic Candidates Look Mighty Familiar], Retrieved May 15, 2018, \"... Malinowski, an assistant secretary of State for President Obama and a State Department official under Clinton ... America, he believes, \"is in deep trouble.\"...\"</ref> Malinowski said he decided to run for office because of what he called the Trump administration's \"effort to take down the Affordable Care Act with no viable replacement. It was the Muslim ban, and attacks on immigrants, it was the tearing up of alliances and commitments internationally. It was the taking down of environmental protections, it was refusing to invest in infrastructure.\"<ref name=\"twsNBCWash11\">May 27, 2018, NBC News Washington (Channel 4), [https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/politics/Former-Obama-Staffers-Elections-483805841.html Fired Up by Trump, Dozens of Former Obama Staffers Run for Office: The surge of Democratic candidates with ties to Obama has the potential to fill state and federal legislatures with like-minded allies], Retrieved May 30, 2018, \"...it was the effort to take down the Affordable Care Act with no viable replacement...\"</ref>\n\nMalinowski supports the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|Affordable Care Act]] and criticized the Republican Party for \"whittling away at the Affordable Care Act year after year.\"<ref name=twsInsiderNJ44>Insider New Jersey, May 12, 2018, Staff writer, [https://www.insidernj.com/cd7-democratic-challenger-malinowski-formally-opens-main-headquarters-pallone/ CD7 Democratic Challenger Malinowski Formally Opens his Main Headquarters with Pallone], Retrieved May 14, 2018, \"... He\u2019ll fight to protect the Affordable Care Act.....\"</ref>  He supports raising the minimum wage to $15 per hour as well as enhanced collective bargaining rights and protections for workers.<ref name=twsNJGlobe11/>  Malinowski sees the Democratic Party, in contrast to the GOP, as promoting fiscal responsibility, law enforcement, family values, and patriotism.<ref name=\"twsWashPost0786\">E. J. Dionne, July 15, 2018, Washington Post, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/does-the-blue-wave-start-in-jersey/2018/07/15/db44a0b2-86e4-11e8-8f6c-46cb43e3f306_story.html?wpisrc=nl_headlines&wpmm=1 Does the blue wave start in Jersey?], Retrieved July 16, 2018</ref>\n\n[[File:Candidate for Congress NJ-7th Tom Malinowski at campaign headquarters speaking with a voter.jpg|thumb|upright|Malinowski at his campaign headquarters in [[Martinsville, New Jersey]]]]\nHis endorsements included the Hunterdon County Democratic Committee<ref name=\"twsNJHills41\">April 27, 2018, New Jersey Hills, [http://www.newjerseyhills.com/hunterdon_review/news/first-lady-tammy-murphy-to-speak-at-county-democratic-brunch/article_a25ed6e9-39ca-56e0-a286-f38ca8e86f59.html First Lady Tammy Murphy to speak at county Democratic brunch on Sunday, April 29], Retrieved May 15, 2018, \"...Tom Malinowski ... endorsed by the HCDC ...\"</ref> and the [[Communications Workers of America]].<ref name=\"twsNJGlobe11\">David Wildstein, April 23, 2018, New Jersey Globe, [https://newjerseyglobe.com/congress/cwa-endorses-malinowski/ CWA Endorses Malinowski], Retrieved May 15, 2018</ref> On June 5, 2018, he faced social worker Peter Jacob and lawyer Goutam Jois.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Jersey's 7th Congressional District election, 2018|url=https://ballotpedia.org/New_Jersey%27s_7th_Congressional_District_election,_2018|accessdate=8 May 2018|publisher=Ballotpedia}}</ref> He defeated Jacob and Jois, receiving 66.8% of the vote and winning all counties in the district<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/new-jersey-house-district-7-primary-election|title=New Jersey Primary Election Results: Seventh House District|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.njelections.org/assets/pdf/election-results/2018/2018-official-primary-results-us-house.pdf|title=Candidates for House of Representatives For PRIMARY ELECTION 06/05/2018 Election,|last=|first=|date=July 20, 2018|website=|access-date=}}</ref> Malinowski went onto to defeat incumbent Republican [[Leonard Lance]].\n\nMalinowski criticized Lance, saying he \"shifted to the right when he was scared of the [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party]] and he's moving to the left when he's scared of his increasingly moderate and energized constituents.\"<ref name=\"twsNJcom441\">Jonathan D. Salant, May 14, 2018, NJ.com, [http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2018/05/how_njs_most_endangered_congressman_is_trying_to_w.html This N.J. Republican is in big trouble because of Trump. Here's what he's doing about it.], Retrieved May 15, 2018</ref> On November 6, Malinowski won the election, receiving 51.7% of the vote. While Malinowski and Lance each carried three of the six counties in the district, Malinowski won the district's shares of Somerset and Union counties by a combined 22,300 votes, more than the overall margin of 16,200 votes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/new-jersey-house-district-7|title=New Jersey\u2019s Seventh House District Election Results: Tom Malinowski vs. Leonard Lance|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.njelections.org/assets/pdf/election-results/2018/2018-official-general-election-results-us-house.pdf|title=Official List Candidates for House of Representatives For GENERAL ELECTION 11/06/2018 Election|last=|first=|date=December 3, 2018|website=|access-date=}}</ref> When he took office in January 2019, he became the first Democrat to represent the 7th and its predecessors since 1961.\n\nOn February 26, 2020, Malinowski stated that he would \u201cabsolutely\u201d support [[Bernie Sanders]] if he were the Democratic Presidential nominee.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mascaro |first1=Lisa |title=Pelosi urges Democratic unity amid Sanders\u2019 campaign surge |url=https://apnews.com/7ef003d3d777ba44bb4e24fed66809f8 |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=The Associated Press |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Committee assignments ===\n\n* [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|'''Committee on Foreign Affairs''']]\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Middle East, North Africa and International Terrorism|Subcommittee on the Middle East, North Africa and International Terrorism]]\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n* [[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|'''Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure''']]\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Highways and Transit|Subcommittee on Highways and Transit]]\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials|Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials]]\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment|Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment]]\n\n=== Caucus memberships ===\n* '''[[LGBT Equality Caucus]]'''\n* '''[[New Democrat Coalition]]'''\n* '''End Corruption Caucus'''<ref name=\"Malinowski Press Release 2020.01.21\">{{cite web |title=Representative Malinowski Leads Fight To End Corruption in Washington |url=https://malinowski.house.gov/media/press-releases/representative-malinowski-leads-fight-end-corruption-washington |website=Tom Malinowski Congressional Web Site |accessdate=27 January 2020 |date=21 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Congressman Max Rose Press Release 2020.01.16\">{{cite web |title=10 Years After Disastrous Citizens United Decision, Rose, Porter, Freshmen Dems Launch New \u2018End Corruption\u2019 Caucus |url=https://maxrose.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=2450 |website=Max Rose Congressional Web Site |accessdate=27 January 2020 |date=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n===Illegal Immigrants===\nAt an August 2019 town hall, Malinowski told constituents that illegal immigrants are needed to mow \"our beautiful lawns\" and perform menial jobs rejected by tech-focused teenagers.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ferrechio |first1=Susan |title=Democratic lawmaker: Illegal immigrants needed to mow 'our beautiful lawns' |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/congress/democratic-lawmaker-illegal-immigrants-needed-to-mow-our-beautiful-lawns |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=Washington Examiner |date=August 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Wulfsohn |first1=Joseph |title=Dem Rep. Tom Malinowski: We need illegal immigrants to 'mow our beautiful lawns' |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/dem-rep-tom-malinowski-illegal-immigrants-to-mow-lawns |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=Fox News |date=August 22, 2019}}</ref> The comments made national headlines and drew backlash from critics who called Malinowski \"out of touch\". Questions were raised as to whether Malinowski pays illegal immigrants to mow his personal lawn.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moritz-Rabson |first1=Daniel |title=DEMOCRATIC CONGRESSMAN SAYS UNDOCUMENTED IMMIGRANTS ARE GOOD FOR 'MOWING OUR BEAUTIFUL LAWNS' |url=https://www.newsweek.com/democratic-congressman-says-undocumented-immigrants-are-good-mowing-our-beautiful-lawns-1455893 |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=Newsweek |date=August 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Prince |first1=Molly |title=WATCH: Dem Lawmaker Says Illegal Immigrants Are Needed To Mow \u2018Our Beautiful Lawns\u2019 |url=https://www.dailywire.com/news/watch-dem-lawmaker-says-illegal-immigrants-are-molly-prince |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=The Daily Wire |date=August 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Meads |first1=Timothy |title=WATCH: Dem Lawmaker Says Illegal Immigrants Are Needed To Mow \u2018Our Beautiful Lawns\u2019 |url=New Jersey Democrat: We Need Illegals To Mow Our 'Beautiful Lawns'e |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=Townhall |date=August 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Impeachment===\nMalinowski was the first member of the New Jersey congressional delegation to call to begin the impeachment inquiry of President [[Donald Trump]] in May 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moran |first1=Tom |title=Malinowski, the first Jersey House member to favor impeachment hearings, explains why|url=https://www.nj.com/opinion/2019/05/malinowski-the-first-jersey-house-member-to-favor-impeachment-hearings-explains-why-moran.html |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=NJ.com |date=May 29, 2019}}</ref> The decision was criticized by Republican operatives.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Biryukov |first1=Nikita |title=Malinowski backs start of impeachment inquiry |url=https://newjerseyglobe.com/congress/malinowski-backs-impeachment/ |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=New Jersey Globe |date=May 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMalinowski owns a home in [[Washington, D.C.]], and was registered to vote there as of March 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pizarro |first1=Max |title=Residency Question Hounds Malinowski on Eve of Union County Vote |url=https://www.insidernj.com/residency-question-hounds-malinowski-eve-union-county-vote/ |accessdate=16 July 2018 |publisher=InsiderNJ |date=March 6, 2018}}</ref> He began renting a home in [[Rocky Hill, New Jersey]], in September 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Brodesser-Akner |first1=Claude |title=What's really going on with all these 'carpetbagger' political attacks in New Jersey? |url=https://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2018/07/hed_whats_really_going_on_with_all_these_carpetbag.html |accessdate=17 July 2018 |publisher=NJ.com |date=July 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Pathe |first1=Simone |title=Could Past DC Residency Be Liability for Some Democrats? |url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/past-dc-residency-liability-democrats |accessdate=16 July 2018 |publisher=Roll Call |date=March 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMalinowski's stepfather [[Blair Clark]] was a journalist. Clark's sister was [[Anne Clark Martindell|Anne Martindell]], a member of the [[New Jersey State Senate]] (1974\u20131977) and a [[List of ambassadors of the United States to New Zealand|United States ambassador to New Zealand]] (1979\u20131981).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wildstein |first1=David |title=Malinowski and the residency thing |url=https://newjerseyglobe.com/section-2/malinowski-residency-thing/ |accessdate= August 8, 2018 |publisher=New Jersey Globe |date=March 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMalinowski has one daughter, Emily.<ref>{{cite news | last1=Muscavage |first1=Nick |title= NJ elections: Democrat Tom Malinowski unseats Republican Leonard Lance in NJ's 7th Congressional District  |url=https://www.mycentraljersey.com/story/news/politics/2018/11/07/nj-7th-district-congress-tom-malinowski-defeats-leonard-lance/1902521002/ |accessdate= March 3, 2020 |publisher= Courier News and Home News Tribune |date=November 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://malinowski.house.gov/ Congressman Tom Malinowski] official U.S. House website\n*[https://malinowskifornj.com/ Tom Malinowski for Congress]\n{{CongLinks|fec=H8NJ07223|votesmart=179645|congbio=M001203|congress=tom-malinowski/M001203}}\n\n{{Commons category|Tomasz P. Malinowski}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Michael Posner (lawyer)|Michael Posner]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]]|years=2014\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Virginia L. Bennett]]<br>{{small|Acting}}}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Leonard Lance]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from New Jersey|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[New Jersey's 7th congressional district]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Elaine Luria]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=383rd}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ben McAdams]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Members of the U.S. House of Representatives}}\n{{NJ-FedRep}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Malinowski, Tom}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Antony's College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:American Rhodes Scholars]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Human Rights Watch people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:New Jersey Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from Princeton, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Rocky Hill, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from S\u0142upsk]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Princeton High School (New Jersey) alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Assistant Secretaries of State]]\n[[Category:United States National Security Council staffers]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:Progressivism in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Thankyoucomeagain5000", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(It is completely absurd to attempt to erase the fact that the 'lawn mowing' event happened. You are free to agree or disagree with the content of his comments/context/etc, but nobody is entitled to erase the immutable fact that it happened. Not a single reference is opinion-oriented, it purely reports on the facts of the event. It was widely covered on dozens of national and local media outlets. This revision includes two additional references.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Malinowski"}
{"title_page": "Class Enemy (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2013 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Class Enemy\n| image          = Class Enemy film poster.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Rok Bi\u010dek]]\n| producer       = [[Aiken Veronika Prosenc]]<br>[[Janez Lapajne]]\n| writer         = [[Nejc Gazvoda]]<br>Rok Bi\u010dek<br>[[Janez Lapajne]]\n| cinematography = Fabio Stoll\n| editing        = [[Janez Lapajne]]<br>Rok Bi\u010dek\n| studio         = Triglav film\n| distributor    = Fivia (in Slovenia)\n| released       = {{Film date|2013|8|30|[[70th Venice International Film Festival|Venice]]|2013|9|12|Slovenia|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 112 minutes\n| country        = Slovenia\n| language       = Slovene<br>German\n}}\n\n'''''Class Enemy''''' ({{lang-sl|'''Razredni sovra\u017enik'''}}) is a 2013 Slovenian [[drama film]] directed by [[Rok Bi\u010dek]]. The film was selected as the Slovenian entry for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] at the [[86th Academy Awards]],<ref name=\"Slovenia\">{{cite web |url=http://www.film-center.si/index.php?module=news&op=show&newsID=984 |title= Razredni sovra\u017enik je leto\u0161nji slovenski kandidat za oskarja |accessdate=25 September 2013|work=Slovenian Film Centre}}</ref> but it was not nominated. It was nominated for the 2014 [[Lux Prize]]. It won the Fedeora Award at the [[70th Venice International Film Festival|28th Venice Critics' Week]].<ref name=Venice>{{cite web|title=\"Class Enemy\" Wins Venice Critics' Week|url=http://www.sloveniatimes.com/slovenian-film-class-enemy-wins-venice-critics-week/6|accessdate=9 September 2014|work=Slovenia Times}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Igor Samobor]] as Robert\n* [[Nata\u0161a Barbara Gra\u010dner]] as Zdenka\n* [[Tja\u0161a \u017deleznik]] as Sa\u0161a\n* [[Ma\u0161a Derganc]] as Nu\u0161a\n* [[Robert Prebil]] as Matja\u017e\n* [[Voranc Boh]] as Luka\n* [[Jan Zupan\u010di\u010d]] as Tadej\n* [[Da\u0161a Cupevski]] as Sabina\n* [[Doroteja Nadrah]] as Mojca\n* [[\u0160pela Novak]] as \u0160pela\n* [[Pia Korbar]] as Maru\u0161a\n* [[Dan David Mrevlje Natla\u010den]] as Primo\u017e\n* [[Jan Vrhovnik]] as Nik\n* [[Kangjing Qiu]] as Chang\n* [[Estera Dvornik]] as Sonja\n* [[Peter Teichmeister]] as janitor\n\n==Awards and accolades==\n''Class Enemy'' was one of three films nominated for the [[European Parliament LUX Prize]] in 2014,<ref name=HRprize>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/girlhood-ida-class-enemy-nominees-721592 |title='Girlhood,' 'Ida,' 'Class Enemy' Nominees for European Parliament's LUX Prize 2014 |author=Scott Roxborough |date=28 July 2014}}</ref> and received the highest number of votes from audiences across Europe<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/news-room/20150701STO72980/lux-prize-2015-the-ten-nominated-films-have-been-revealed |quote='''Audience Mention for 2014 Lux Prize''' The film of the 2014 Lux Prize competition that received the highest number of votes from audiences across Europe has also been announced: Slovenian film Class Enemy by Rok Bicek. |date=9 July 2015 |title=Lux Prize 2015: the ten nominated films have been revealed |accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref> although the prize winner (chosen by a ballot of MEPs) was ''[[Ida (film)|Ida]]''.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/news-room/20141212IPR01104/ida-wins-2014-lux-film-prize |title=\"Ida\" wins 2014 LUX Film Prize   |publisher=European Parliament |date=17 December 2014 |accessdate=24 September 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThe FEDEORA (Federation of Film Critics of Europe and the Mediterranean) jury awarded ''Class Enemy'' its prize for Best Film of the International Critics' Week at Venice in 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fedeora.eu/ |title=FEDEORA |accessdate=24 September 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110112041936/http://www.fedeora.eu/ |archive-date=12 January 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=HRprize/>\n\nAt the [[Festival of Slovenian Film]] in September 2013, ''Class Enemy'' won seven [[Vesna]] awards: Best Film, Best Lead Actor (Igor Samobor), Best Supporting Actress (Barbara Gra\u010dner), Best Cinematography (Fabio Stoll), Best Costume Design ( Bistra Borak), the audience award, and the critics' award.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cineuropa.org/nw.aspx?t=newsdetail&l=en&did=244248 |website=Cineuropa |author=Vladan Petkovic |title=''Class Enemy'' triumphs at Slovenian awards |date=17 September 2013 |accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2013 [[International Film Festival of Bratislava]], ''Class Enemy'' won the Grand Prix, the Audience Award, the Award for Best Actor, and the FIPRESCI Prize.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cineuropa.org/nw.aspx?t=newsdetail&l=en&did=248148 |title=Slovenian ''Class Enemy'' dominated IFF Bratislava |author=Martin Kudl\u00e1\u010d |date=21 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nIt also won the FIPRESCI International Film Critics Prize at the [[Panorama of European Cinema]] in Athens in November 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fipresci.org/festival-reports/2013/panorama-of-european-cinema/lessons-on-life-and-death |title=Lessons on Life and Death |author=Aleksander Huser |year=2013 |accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of submissions to the 86th Academy Awards for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n* [[List of Slovenian submissions for the Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|3187076|Class Enemy}}\n* [http://www.cineuropa.org/f.aspx?t=film&l=en&did=242742 ''Class Enemy'' at Cineuropa]\n* [http://www.luxprize.eu/news/focus-razredni-sovra%C5%BEnik-class-enemy Focus on Razredni Sovra\u017enik (Class Enemy)] (European Parliament / LUX Prize)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Class Enemy}}\n[[Category:2013 films]]\n[[Category:2013 drama films]]\n[[Category:German-language films]]\n[[Category:Slovenian films]]\n[[Category:Slovene-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about education]]\n[[Category:Films about suicide]]\n[[Category:Slovenian drama films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2013 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Class Enemy\n| image          = Class Enemy film poster.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Rok Bi\u010dek]]\n| producer       = [[Aiken Veronika Prosenc]]<br>[[Janez Lapajne]]\n| writer         = [[Nejc Gazvoda]]<br>Rok Bi\u010dek<br>[[Janez Lapajne]]\n| cinematography = Fabio Stoll\n| editing        = [[Janez Lapajne]]<br>Rok Bi\u010dek\n| studio         = Triglav film\n| distributor    = Fivia (in Slovenia)\n| released       = {{Film date|2013|8|30|[[70th Venice International Film Festival|Venice]]|2013|9|12|Slovenia|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 112 minutes\n| country        = Slovenia\n| language       = Slovene<br>German\n}}\n\n'''''Class Enemy''''' ({{lang-sl|'''Razredni sovra\u017enik'''}}) is a 2013 Slovenian [[drama film]] directed by [[Rok Bi\u010dek]]. The film was selected as the Slovenian entry for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] at the [[86th Academy Awards]],<ref name=\"Slovenia\">{{cite web |url=http://www.film-center.si/index.php?module=news&op=show&newsID=984 |title= Razredni sovra\u017enik je leto\u0161nji slovenski kandidat za oskarja |accessdate=25 September 2013|work=Slovenian Film Centre}}</ref> but it was not nominated. It was nominated for the 2014 [[Lux Prize]]. It won the Fedeora Award at the [[70th Venice International Film Festival|28th Venice Critics' Week]].<ref name=Venice>{{cite web|title=\"Class Enemy\" Wins Venice Critics' Week|url=http://www.sloveniatimes.com/slovenian-film-class-enemy-wins-venice-critics-week/6|accessdate=9 September 2014|work=Slovenia Times}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Igor Samobor]] as Robert\n* [[Nata\u0161a Barbara Gra\u010dner]] as Zdenka\n* [[Tja\u0161a \u017deleznik]] as Sa\u0161a\n* [[Ma\u0161a Derganc]] as Nu\u0161a\n* [[Robert Prebil]] as Matja\u017e\n* [[Voranc Boh]] as Luka\n* [[Jan Zupan\u010di\u010d]] as Tadej\n* [[Da\u0161a Cupevski]] as Sabina\n* [[Doroteja Nadrah]] as Mojca\n* [[\u0160pela Novak]] as \u0160pela\n* [[Pia Korbar]] as Maru\u0161a\n* [[Dan David Mrevlje Natla\u010den]] as Primo\u017e\n* [[Jan Vrhovnik]] as Nik\n* [[Kangjing Qiu]] as Chang\n* [[Estera Dvornik]] as Sonja\n* [[Peter Teichmeister]] as janitor\n\n==Awards and accolades==\n''Class Enemy'' was one of three films nominated for the [[European Parliament LUX Prize]] in 2014,<ref name=HRprize>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/girlhood-ida-class-enemy-nominees-721592 |title='Girlhood,' 'Ida,' 'Class Enemy' Nominees for European Parliament's LUX Prize 2014 |author=Scott Roxborough |date=28 July 2014}}</ref> and received the highest number of votes from audiences across Europe<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/news-room/20150701STO72980/lux-prize-2015-the-ten-nominated-films-have-been-revealed |quote='''Audience Mention for 2014 Lux Prize''' The film of the 2014 Lux Prize competition that received the highest number of votes from audiences across Europe has also been announced: Slovenian film Class Enemy by Rok Bicek. |date=9 July 2015 |title=Lux Prize 2015: the ten nominated films have been revealed |accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref> although the prize winner (chosen by a ballot of MEPs) was ''[[Ida (film)|Ida]]''.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/news-room/20141212IPR01104/ida-wins-2014-lux-film-prize |title=\"Ida\" wins 2014 LUX Film Prize   |publisher=European Parliament |date=17 December 2014 |accessdate=24 September 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThe FEDEORA (Federation of Film Critics of Europe and the Mediterranean) jury awarded ''Class Enemy'' its prize for Best Film of the International Critics' Week at Venice in 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fedeora.eu/ |title=FEDEORA |accessdate=24 September 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110112041936/http://www.fedeora.eu/ |archive-date=12 January 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=HRprize/>\n\nAt the [[Festival of Slovenian Film]] in September 2013, ''Class Enemy'' won seven [[Vesna]] awards: Best Film, Best Lead Actor (Igor Samobor), Best Supporting Actress (Barbara Gra\u010dner), Best Cinematography (Fabio Stoll), Best Costume Design ( Bistra Borak), the audience award, and the critics' award.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cineuropa.org/nw.aspx?t=newsdetail&l=en&did=244248 |website=Cineuropa |author=Vladan Petkovic |title=''Class Enemy'' triumphs at Slovenian awards |date=17 September 2013 |accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2013 [[International Film Festival of Bratislava]], ''Class Enemy'' won the Grand Prix, the Audience Award, the Award for Best Actor, and the FIPRESCI Prize.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cineuropa.org/nw.aspx?t=newsdetail&l=en&did=248148 |title=Slovenian ''Class Enemy'' dominated IFF Bratislava |author=Martin Kudl\u00e1\u010d |date=21 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nIt also won the FIPRESCI International Film Critics Prize at the [[Panorama of European Cinema]] in Athens in November 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fipresci.org/festival-reports/2013/panorama-of-european-cinema/lessons-on-life-and-death |title=Lessons on Life and Death |author=Aleksander Huser |year=2013 |accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of submissions to the 86th Academy Awards for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n* [[List of Slovenian submissions for the Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|3187076|Class Enemy}}\n* [http://www.cineuropa.org/f.aspx?t=film&l=en&did=242742 ''Class Enemy'' at Cineuropa]\n* [http://www.luxprize.eu/news/focus-razredni-sovra%C5%BEnik-class-enemy Focus on Razredni Sovra\u017enik (Class Enemy)] (European Parliament / LUX Prize)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Class 